{For every French player, the Advance Variation and the Exchange Variation are responsible for countless headaches — and even a few sleepless nights. No matter what you play against 3.Nc3 or 3.Nd2, you simply can't avoid these systems. In this database, we offer you a modern and fresh repertoire designed to neutralize White’s ideas while keeping winning chances alive. The lines have been carefully selected to be easy to play, easy to remember, and — most importantly — dynamic. You won’t just survive these systems. You’ll be ready to outplay your opponents and play for three results, not just a draw.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 (2. d3 {Against the King’s Indian Attack, Black can easily lose games simply by lacking a clear plan. It’s a system that punishes hesitation and passive play. That’s why we dedicate Chapter 9 to this setup, offering one of the most practical and straightforward solutions available for Black — a line that keeps things under control while leaving no room for surprises.}) (2. Qe2 {This move is important, as White prevents our main French idea of pushing ...d5. We’ll take a closer look at how to handle it in Chapter 10.}) (2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 {The Two Knights Variation can be an interesting weapon for White against the Caro-Kann — but not against the French. That said, to make sure it stays uninteresting for White, you need to know exactly how to deal with it. That’s why we’ll cover it in Chapter 11.}) (2. b3 {Moves like 2.b3 — and other early sidelines — are especially popular in blitz and bullet games. If you mostly play classical chess, it’s not vital to be deeply prepared against them. But if you enjoy faster time controls, it’s definitely worth having a clear and easy-to-remember solution for each of these tricky lines. That’s exactly what Chapter 12 is for!}) 2... d5 3. e5 {The Advance Variation is extremely important, as White immediately grabs space — and if Black isn’t well-prepared, it’s easy to end up in a passive position for a long time. But don’t worry: once you’ve studied the first six chapters of this course, that will never be a problem again.} (3. Bd3 {We can safely call this the “Lazy Variation.” White hopes to sidestep mainline theory with 3.Bd3 and just get a slightly better position with minimal effort. Our job is to punish this attitude. In Chapter 8, we’ll show how to seize the initiative early and make White regret not playing real theory.}) (3. exd5 {The Exchange Variation is unpleasant for many French players, simply because they feel they have no winning chances. Some players even choose the Exchange French to win — including myself ! The good news is: having played this line for a long time with White, I can now show you the best system for Black — one that avoids all the usual problems and keeps real winning chances on the board. We’ll dive into it in Chapter 7.} exd5 4. Nf3 Bd6) 3... c5 4. c3 (4. Nf3 {Other sidelines will be discussed in Chapter 1, where we’ll also take a look at two recent inventions by Abdusattorov in his games against Mendonca.}) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Bb6] This is our recommendation — and for good reason. It’s the easiest line to play, and Black also keeps real winning chances.} 6. a3 {This is White’s most strategically principled continuation.} (6. Bd3 {The mythological French Gambit will be covered in Chapter 2, making sure you’ll have no trouble facing it — whether it’s the classic version or one of its modern twists.}) (6. Be2 {White's most solid line.} Nh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] This is our recommendation because it leads to positions where we can rely on our understanding, not on endless memorization of variations. We will study it in Chapter 3.} (6... cxd4 {[%csl Rd4]} 7. cxd4 Nh6 {[%csl Rh6] This is Black’s most common continuation, but it comes with several drawbacks: you need to memorize a huge number of lines, be ready for all kinds of last-minute surprises, and — perhaps worst of all — Black is often just playing for a draw. In short, it’s much better to go for 6...Nh6.})) 6... Bd7 {[%csl Bd7] This is our recommendation, and we’ll follow — and update — the direction shown by GM Ferenc Berkes during his incredible run at the 2023 World Cup.} 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 {Now, White has three lines:} 9. Be2 {This is our recommendation, and we’ll follow — and update — the direction shown by GM Ferenc Berkes during his incredible run at the 2023 World Cup.} (9. Be3 {[%csl Ge3] An important line in itself — but even more so after the 2024 discovery introduced by Sindarov in his game against Praggnanandhaa at the 2024 Olympiad.}) (9. Bb2 {White’s most common continuation — and a very important one. We’ll take a closer look at it in Chapter 6.}) *

