{[%evp 0,28,34,18,30,38,24,14,2,6,2,10,8,3,16,15,22,13,2,9,33,37,0,-5,-13,-13,2,-10,3,3,8]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 (3. exd5 exd5 {I play the French exchange with White and Black, and very rarely it ends with a boring draw.} 4. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3] This is White's most natural move and also the best one, in my opinion.} (4. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2] White can play with Bd3-Ne2, but it's harmless:} Bd6 5. Ne2 Nf6 {[%csl Gf6] When White's knight is on f3, we will develop the knight on e7, but now that White's knight is on e2, we will go on f6.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Bf4 Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 $11) 4... Bd6 {When I am White, I play here 5.Bd3, but 5.c4 is more popular nowadays.} 5. Bd3 {I like this continuation because Black needs experience and preparation to fully equalize.} (5. c4 {This is how top players usually play nowadays.} Nf6 {if you don't want to transpose in QGA for Black, you can also play Nf6.} 6. c5 {modern continuation, more interesting than 6.Nc3.} Be7 {[%cal Gb7b6] our idea is now b6, and White should find a clever move against it.} 7. Qa4+ $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Rb7b6] This is considered the most interesting continuation for White.} (7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Be3 (9. b4 a5 $1 $15) (9. cxb6 axb6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6] c5-Nc6 next.}) 9... bxc5 10. dxc5 a5 {very useful move, and we can continue with Ba6 or Bg4, according to the situation.}) 7... Bd7 8. Qc2 (8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb3] doesn't make sense, because after} b6 $15 {[%csl Rc5] White's c5 pawn is not protected.}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 (9. Bd3 $6 {not good for concrete reasons:} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 10. a3 (10. O-O Nb4 $15) 10... Re8 $1 $146 11. O-O Bg4 $36 {[%csl Rd4] White has problems with d4.}) 9... Re8 $1 $146 {Strong Novelty. Re8 is a very useful move, and we will act according to White's next move.} 10. Be2 {White gives priority to the development, but with Be2 only because Bd3 is bad for concrete reasons.} Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gd7f5] my idea is to play Bf5. Once we play it, our position will be absolutely fine, for example:}) 5... Nc6 {[%csl Gc6] I recommend to play Nc6.} 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 {most common and natural move.} Bf5 $1 {this is the most accurate continuation. Of course, exchanging the bishops is nice, but the big question is to understand if it works against White's concrete tries.} (7... O-O {would be nice, but as I indicate in my course "Exchange French for White", after} 8. Nh4 $1 $40 {White gets a strong kingside initiative.}) 8. Bxf5 {only critical move.} Nxf5 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7] we need to spend another tempo to protect b7.} b6 10. Re1+ {critical position.} Nce7 $1 {[%csl Ge7,Rf5] This is the best. It's a bit strange because the knight on f5 looks very shaky, but it works concretely. leads to the same as 9.Qb3.} 11. g4 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4] very important, we are not afraid of Bxh6.} 12. Bxh6 gxh6 $132 {[%csl Rf4,Rg4] We are not worse because White has problems with g4 and with the f4 square.}) 3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 (6. Bd3 {The topic of this chapter. This gambit has been played in 12000 games, so our goal is to keep it simple, and play with Black without memorising too many forced lines.} cxd4 {White has two options: 7.cxd4 is the old way and 7.0-0 is the modern way.} 7. O-O $5 {The modern approach, White is waiting for dxc3 so that the knight can develop to an active square.} (7. cxd4 {The old way.} Bd7 8. O-O {This was White's original idea.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 $6 {The old main line is just not great.} Qxd4 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] White has Nb5 ideas.} a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rc3b5] Important move, to defend the b5 square.} 11. Qe2 Ne7 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] White's most common idea, to continue with f4.} (12. Rd1 Qh4 $17 {Big advantage, -1.}) 12... Nc6 13. f4 Nb4 {Very simple way to play.}) 7... Bd7 $5 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Rb1d2,Gd4c3] Black's strategy is very simple. We are waiting for Nbd2, only then we are going to take on c3 (since the knight cannot recapture).} (7... dxc3 $6 {We don't go for this, we will play positionally instead.} 8. Nxc3 $13 {[%csl Gc3] The knight on c3 stays well, position is very unclear.}) 8. Re1 {White usually starts with this, still hoping for dxc3-Nxc3.} Nge7 {Finish development.} 9. h4 $1 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Re7g6,Gh4h5] The best move for White, prophylaxis against Ng6 (which is met with h5).} (9. Nbd2 {We follow the rule:} dxc3 $1 {And White is forced to capture with the pawn.} 10. bxc3 Ng6 {[%csl Re5] To immediately pressure the e5 pawn.}) 9... a6 {I like this useful move the most.} 10. h5 {The most common continuation.} (10. Nbd2 {is again met with} dxc3 $1 {Key positional idea.} 11. bxc3 Ng6 $132) 10... g6 $1 $13 {[%csl Bg6] This is why I chose 9...a6 instead of 9...h6.}) (6. Be2 {The topic of this chapter. Not a dangerous line, but Black needs to decide what to do.} Nh6 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc5d4,Rc3d4,Rb1c3] This is my recommendation. Same idea as in the main line, but we delay cxd4 cxd4 so that White's knight cannot develop to c3.} 7. Bxh6 {Critical capture to ruin the structure.} (7. O-O {Possible move.} cxd4 8. cxd4 $2 {Automatic move, but probably just losing.} (8. Bxh6 $1 {Only move.} dxc3 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc3b2] Strong intermezzo.} (8... gxh6 $2 {is not good.} 9. cxd4 Qxb2 10. Nbd2 $36 {And we transpose to a line that I don't like for Black.})) 8... Nf5 $1 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Rc1e3,Rb6b2] White cannot defend the d4 pawn, resigning is understandable.}) 7... gxh6 {[%cal Rb1c3] But you see, compared to the main line, no Nc3 is possible, so this makes it an improved version for Black.} 8. Qd2 {Only good move, but logical one.} Bg7 9. O-O {Necessary move.} O-O {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8d7] Black has an easy plan: f7-f6.} 10. Na3 {White plays this automatic move, 176 games out of 180. White cannot play without short castle, check the main line.} cxd4 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Gc3][%cal Rb1a3,Gb1c3] Good moment to take, and good understanding, because White's knight cannot develop to c3 anymore.} 11. cxd4 f6 $5 {This is always necessary move for Black, so better to do it immediately.} 12. exf6 Rxf6 {The key position of this chapter.} 13. Nc2 {White improves the knight, no other logical moves. Be careful with Black now!} a5 $1 {[%csl Bc6,Ye5][%cal Rb2b4,Bc6e5] The most precise move, important to stop White's key strategical idea.} (13... Bd7 $6 {is almost an automatic move, but it's a small mistake!} 14. b4 $1 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gb4b5,Rc6e7,Gf3e5] Important idea for White, the plan is b5-Ne5, securing a small advantage.})) 6... Bd7 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc1,Gd4][%cal Gc6d4]} 9. Bb2 {This is White's most common continuation.} (9. Be2 {This move is not so critical, but by analyzing it, we can learn some typical ideas of the position.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black's typical idea is Nf5-Be7-00. But this plan works only in theory; in practice, it's very rare that we will execute it because something always happens in between.} 10. O-O Nf5 {White can defend the d4 pawn by placing the bishop on e3 or on b2.} 11. Bb2 (11. Be3 {Black has now a very simple continuation:} Nxe3 12. fxe3 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7b5] our idea is Bb5.}) 11... Be7 12. Qd2 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gf1d1] White's most common continuation. The idea is to protect the d4 pawn by playing Rd1, and then develop the knight on c3.} (12. g4 Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. Qd3 {[%cal Gb1d2] White prepares Nd2, which was not possible immediately due to the hanging pawn on d4.} f6 $1 15. Nd2 fxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17. Nf3 Be7 $36 {[%csl Rg4] Black's position is preferable, at least because the pawn on g4 is misplaced.}) (12. Qd3 {[%cal Gb1d2] Was played by Caruana.} Na5 $1 13. Nbd2 Nc4 14. Nxc4 dxc4 $132) 12... h5 $1 13. Rd1 $2 {White's idea, but a mistake!} g5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh8g8,Ge7g5] We can continue with g4 and then eventually Rg8-Bg5.}) (9. Be3 {Against Be3, we lose our Na5 ideas, but we can play for Nh6-Ng4, targeting White's bishop on e3.} Nh6 10. Bd3 {White prevents Nf5.} (10. Bxh6 $2 {Bad move.} gxh6 11. Be2 Rg8 $1 $146 {Strong move.} 12. O-O Rg4 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) 10... Ng4 $1 {The correct way to attack e3.} 11. O-O {The most played by far.} Be7 {Better way to start.} 12. Nbd2 {The logical move.} Nxe3 {Good moment to capture.} 13. fxe3 {Be careful, Black has an important move:} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Bb8][%cal Gd7b5] Key starting move, the positional idea is Bb5.} 14. Qe2 {Critical move against Bb5.} a6 $5 {[%cal Gd7b5] I think this is more human, and it's easier to play and understand. Transposes to 11.0-0.}) 9... Nge7 {Our idea is to continue with Nf5, creating pressure against White's pawn on d4. But we also have the Na5-Nc4 idea.} (9... Na5 $6 {is premature because of} 10. Nbd2 {where Black tried} Nc4 {but after} 11. Nxc4 dxc4 12. Rc1 Qa6 13. d5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Ne7 15. Qd2 $1 b5 16. Be2 Be6 17. O-O $14 {Our position is unpleasant to play.}) 10. Nc3 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gc3a4,Ya4c5] White's most serious continuation. The idea is Na4-Nc5.} (10. Nbd2 $6 {This is not a good move for concrete reasons:} Nf5 11. Nb3 a5 $1 {very important idea to remember.} 12. b5 a4 $1 (12... Na7 $2 {Would be a huge positional mistake, because after} 13. a4 $1 $16 {White is strategically much better.})) 10... Na5 {White wants to have a knight on c5, and we want to have a knight on c4.} 11. Na4 {White's main idea.} Qc6 12. Nc5 Nc4 {This is a very important position for the evaluation of the variation.} 13. Bc1 {[%cal Gc1h6] From c1 the bishop still has an influence on the kingside.} (13. Bc3 $5 {Compared to 13.Bc1, the bishop on c3 may be useful against a5, or in the case of f5-exf6-Bxf6, White's pawn on d4 will be more protected.} b6 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bd3 g6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gf8h6] Strong play shown by Pragg. As White's bishop is on c3, Black idea is to continue with h5-Bh6.}) 13... b6 14. Nxd7 (14. Nb3 $2 {This is not how White should play, after} Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gd7a4] Black will continue with Ba4 and a5, and our position is already better.}) 14... Qxd7 $132 *

