{[%evp 0,28,29,13,36,30,35,13,10,0,-3,-3,13,-29,3,-7,-5,3,-9,-9,-5,-5,-5,-16,-8,-5,-22,-10,-13,-13,-13]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 (4. Qg4 $2 {Just bad move.} Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Bd3 (6. Nxd4 Nxe5 $17) 6... h5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] First move you need to remember.} 7. Qf4 {Critical, to target the f7 pawn.} (7. Qg3 {is too slow, everything comes with tempo now:} h4 8. Qg4 Nh6 9. Bxh6 Rxh6 10. O-O f6 $1 $19 {[%csl Bf6] The most precise, Black is just winning.} (10... Bd7 $17 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge8c8] also good enough.})) 7... f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] Strong move, Black has a huge advantage.} (7... Bd7 8. O-O Qc7 $13 {[%csl Gf4,Cf7,Gg3][%cal Ge8c8,Gf4f7] Not so clear, compared to 7.Qg3, because the queen is more active.}) 8. Bg6+ Kd7 $17 {[%csl Gd5,Gd7,Ge6][%cal Gf6e5,Gc6e5,Gg8f6,Gf8d6] -1.50 evaluation.}) (4. Nf3 Nc6 {More practical, because yes, we allow White to transpose to the main Advance French, but anyways we need to know it, so we are not scared of it.} (4... cxd4 {is more precise according to the engine, but you need to study one extra line.} 5. Nxd4 $5 {Extra line, you need to learn.} (5. Bd3 Nc6 {transposes to 4...Nc6.})) 5. Bd3 {Logical move, if White chooses the 4.Nf3 move order.} (5. c3 {The best, transposing to the main position.}) 5... cxd4 6. O-O {[%csl Cd4,Ge5][%cal Gf1e1,Gc1f4,Gb1d2,Gd2b3,Gb3d4] White plays for development.} f6 $5 {The most practical move.} 7. Bb5 $1 {The best move, to regain material.} (7. Bf4 $2 {Huge mistake.} g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Typical.} 8. Bg3 f5 $17 {-1 already.}) (7. Qe2 $6 {also bad.} Bc5 $1 {Just develop and overprotect d4.} (7... fxe5 {The main line, but White can somehow play it.} 8. Nxe5 $44) 8. Nbd2 Nge7 9. Nb3 Bb6 $15 {New position, Black is slightly better.}) 7... Bd7 8. Bxc6 {[%csl Ge5] Logical.} bxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gd7,Oe6][%cal Gc6c5,Gd7e6] Correct recapture for the Advance french, Black plays for a big solid center.} 9. Qxd4 Qb6 {[%csl Gb6] Very straightforward solution.} 10. Qg4 {To stop Black's bishop from developing.} (10. Qf4 Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6] Target the pawn and follow the queen.} 11. Re1 Ne7 12. Qd4 Ng6 {Interesting, Black has huge compensation, after:} (12... Nf5 $5 {good enough.}) 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Qxf6 Be7 15. Qc3 Rg8 $36 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4] Typical french play with initiative.}) 10... Ne7 $146 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Qh5+ {Critical line:} Ng6 13. Nh4 Rg8 14. Qxh7 Rg7 15. Qh5 O-O-O $3 {Key move.} 16. Nxg6 Be8 $1 {[%csl Be8] The point.} 17. Qh3 Rxg6 18. Qxe6+ Bd7 19. Qf7 Rg4 20. h3 $1 Rg7 21. Qxf6 Rg8 {[%cal Gf8c5] 2 pawns down, but very big initiative:} 22. Be3 Qb7 $36 {White can lose this position in a few moves.} 23. Kh1 $4 {Logical, but already losing!} Bxh3 $3 24. gxh3 Qd7 25. Qf3 Rh8 26. Kg2 Be7 $19 {[%cal Gd8g8] White can resign.}) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Cb6d4,Rc1e3,Cb6b2] the idea is to increase the pressure on d4 and eventually undermine White's centre. The queen also attacks the b2-square, so White's dark-square bishop cannot easily defend the d4-pawn without losing the b2-pawn. White's most common replies are 6.a3, 6.Be2 and 6.Bd3.} 6. Na3 (6. Bd3 {[%csl Cd3,Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] is the French Gambit, and we will analyze it in Chapter 2.}) (6. Be2 {[%csl Ce2][%cal Ge1g1] is the other alternative, aiming simply to castle. We will analyze it in Chapter 3.}) (6. a3 {[%csl Ca3][%cal Gb2b4] is currently the most important line in the Advance: it prepares 7.b4, gaining space on the queenside. We will analyze it in Chapters 4-5-6.}) (6. b3 $2 {Just bad move.} cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re1] White is losing d4.} 8. Bd2 Nxd4 $17) (6. g3 {was played by Abdusattorov against Mendonca, Qatar 2024.} cxd4 $1 {Good reaction here.} (6... Bd7 {Black's reply, but after} 7. Bh3 $132 {White has a game, in the end Abdusattorov won.}) 7. cxd4 Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f5] To put pressure on d4.} 8. Bh3 {was maybe White's idea, but} (8. Bg2 $2 {just drops d4.} Nf5 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) (8. Nc3 Nf5 9. Ne2 {is of course, too passive.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 O-O $36 {[%cal Gf7f6] White needs to think about equality.}) (8. Bxh6 $2 Qxb2 $1 {Intermezzo.} 9. Nbd2 gxh6 $17 {[%csl Rg3] -1 evaluation.}) 8... Nf5 $1 {Any French player should now that this structure is good for Black.} 9. Bxf5 exf5 10. Nc3 Be6 11. O-O h6 $132 {Very good position without theory, you can play for 3 results.}) (6. a4 {Some months later, it is Abdusattorov-Mendonca, Wjik aan Zee 2025, and again White won!} cxd4 7. cxd4 Nge7 $5 {[%csl Ge7,Rh6][%cal Rg8h6,Rc1h6] The easiest move, in my opinion, same idea, but it doesn't allow Bxh6.} (7... Nh6 $6 {Mendonca analyzed the previous game, and thought that this reaction is always good, but it's a mistake now!} 8. Bxh6 $1 Qxb2 9. Nbd2 gxh6 {[%csl Ga4] Compared to 6.g3, the pawn is very useful on a4.} 10. Bb5 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb5] White is slightly better.}) 8. Na3 {The most logical move, to put the knight to c2.} Nf5 9. Nc2 Bd7 {Black can just paly a game of chess:} 10. Be2 Na5 $5 {[%cal Ga5b3] Typical idea.} 11. Bd2 $1 {Best move.} (11. O-O $2 Nb3 $1 $17) 11... Nc4 $1 {Good move now.} (11... Nb3 $6 12. a5 $1 $132 {[%csl Ga5,Rb6] is the idea.}) 12. a5 (12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Bc3 Bc6 $132 {[%csl Gc6] Very interesting position, the ''passive french bishop'' is now a monster.}) 12... Qb3 13. Bc3 Rc8 $132 {[%cal Gd7b5] Position for 3 results.}) 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ $5 {Simple solution.} 8. Bd2 Nge7 9. Nb5 {White fights for the d6 square.} (9. Nc2 {Logical, now we can win a pawn:} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxb2 11. Bd3 Qb6 12. O-O h6 13. Rab1 Qa5 $44 {White has some compensation, but Black is pawn up after all.}) (9. Bd3 $2 {Not possible.} Nxd4 $1 $17) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. Be2 f6 $1 {Typical stuff.} 12. exf6 Rxf6 13. Nc3 {Necessary.} (13. O-O $2 {is met with} Rxf3 $3 {Instructive exchange sacrifice.} 14. gxf3 a6 15. Nc3 Nxd4 $15 {Black is better.}) 13... Bd7 14. O-O Be8 $132 {Dream version of the French.} *

