{[%evp 0,58,27,28,36,36,30,13,13,0,0,0,0,7,-3,-39,-61,-69,-31,-76,-63,-70,-53,-84,-73,-69,-75,-75,-71,-87,-68,-80,-63,-63,-56,-103,-79,-47,-48,-67,-56,-128,-30,-30,-30,10,-4,-17,22,-12,51,27,27,26,24,15,15,17,6,22,13]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 {The topic of this chapter. This gambit has been played in 12000 games, so our goal is to keep it simple, and play with Black without memorising too many forced lines.} cxd4 {White has two options: 7.cxd4 is the old way and 7.0-0 is the modern way.} 7. O-O $5 {The modern approach, White is waiting for dxc3 so that the knight can develop to an active square.} (7. cxd4 {The old way.} Bd7 8. Be2 $5 {This is probably White's most interesting move nowadays.} (8. O-O {This was White's original idea.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 $6 {The old main line is just not great.} (9. Nbd2 {Not the oldest and not the newest move.} Nxf3+ {This is extremely safe line.} (9... Bc5 $5 {This is an ambitious line.} 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nf3 Ne7 {And it's tough to play for White.} 12. Bd2 $1 {Best move for the engine, really mysterious.} f5 $36 {Black plays for the initiative.}) 10. Nxf3 Bb5 {The only problem is that if White plays well, it will be equal.} 11. Be3 Qa6 12. Bxb5+ Qxb5 13. Nd4 {White has good development, and while Black will try to play Ne7-Nc6, in the meantime White can regain the pawn.} (13. Rc1 {Be careful if White starts with this move:} Qd7 $1 {First, to get the queen to safety and stop Rc7.} (13... Ne7 $2 {is bad.} 14. Rc7 $16 {[%csl Rb5,Gc7,Rf7,Gg5][%cal Gf3d4,Gf3g5,Re7c6] The rook is very active here.}) 14. Nd4 Ne7 {Transposes to 13.Nd4.}) 13... Qd7 14. Rc1 Ne7 15. Qd3 {Normal scenario could be:} Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rc2 {White wants to double the rooks.} Be7 18. Rfc1 Rc8 19. Qa6 {White regainst the pawn.} c5 $1 {The best way to give it back.} 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Rxc5 Bxc5 22. Rxc5 O-O $11 {Just equal endgame.}) 9... Qxd4 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] White has Nb5 ideas.} (10. Qe2 {has been tried in some games, White's idea is Nd2-Nf3, but it's also quite bad.} a6 11. Nd2 Qa4 $1 $146 {[%csl Ga4,Rd4][%cal Gd7b5] Very precise move, prophylaxis against the knight moves and also prepares Bb5.} (11... Ne7 $6 {This is not precise, White has full compensation after} 12. Nb3 $11 {or 12.Nf3.}) 12. b3 (12. Nb3 Bb5 $17 {Same story.}) (12. Nf3 Bb5 $17 {This is the point.}) 12... Qa5 13. a4 {To stop Bb5, but now just finish development.} (13. Nf3 {is still met with} Bb5 $17) 13... Ne7 $15 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge7c6] The b4 square is weak.}) 10... a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rc3b5] Important move, to defend the b5 square.} 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 {was tried in some recent games, but it's also quite bad.} Ne7 12. Be3 {White sacrifices the second pawn.} Qxe5 13. Bc5 Qf6 {Simple move.} (13... Qg5 {is the same, just with one extra move.} 14. Be3 {The best.} Qe5 15. Bc5 Qf6 {see 13...Qf6.}) 14. Qb3 Bc6 $17 {[%cal Ge7g6] No problem and better for Black, of course.}) 11... Ne7 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] White's most common idea, to continue with f4.} (12. Be3 {is bad.} Qxe5 $17) (12. Rd1 Qh4 $17 {Big advantage, -1.}) 12... Nc6 13. f4 Nb4 {Very simple way to play.} 14. Rd1 {White's main try.} (14. Bb1 $6 {is met with} Qc4 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4] In the endgame, Black has a huge advantage, otherwise d4 is coming.} 15. Qd1 d4 16. Ne4 d3 $19 {Game over, -2 something.}) 14... Bc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] This is even more precise.} (14... Nxd3 {is a solid option.} 15. Rxd3 Qb6 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 $15 {[%cal Rf4f5,Gd7c6] This is slightly better for Black, White has some compensation, but not full.}) 15. Bxa6 Qf2 {[%csl Gf2] This is the point, material is equal now, but Black has a huge positional advantage.} 16. Qxf2 Bxf2 $17 {That's why this line is no longer played nowadays.}) (8. Bc2 $6 {Bad way to defend the pawn.} Nb4 $1 9. O-O Nxc2 10. Qxc2 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5,Ga8c8] This is slightly better for Black, pair of bishops for free.}) 8... Nh6 $1 {Much simpler move, the knight gets to f5, but not allowing Na3-Nc2.} (8... Nge7 $6 {is a common mistake.} 9. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rf8] The knight can develop to a3, because the bishop is blocked by the knight.} Nf5 10. Nc2 $132 {Black is fine, but it's a game, it could be a serious line for White.}) 9. Nc3 {This is maximum draw for White.} (9. Bxh6 {The only extra option.} Qxb2 $1 {Usual intermezzo.} 10. Nbd2 {The only good move.} (10. Bxg7 $2 {In majority of games, White took, but it's just bad.} Bxg7 $19 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rb1d2,Gc6d4] Positionally and tactically losing for White.}) 10... gxh6 11. O-O $1 $146 {The best move.} (11. Rb1 $2 {is how everybody played in this position, but after} Qxa2 12. Rxb7 Nb4 $1 {Black has a big advantage.} 13. O-O O-O-O $19 {[%csl Rb7] The rook is trapped.}) 11... b6 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7] Useful prophylactic move.} 12. Nb3 $1 Rc8 13. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] is how engine is trying to play it.} a5 $36 {[%cal Ga5a4] With idea a4, White has some kind of compensation, but not full of course, -0.40 for the engine.}) (9. Na3 $6 {This is not the way now.} Bb4+ $5 {Good intermezzo.} (9... Bxa3 {is also possible of course.} 10. bxa3 Nf5 $15 {[%csl Rd4] Problems with d4 pawn.}) 10. Kf1 O-O $15 {Just slightly better position, similar to the 6.Be2 line.}) 9... Nf5 10. Na4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Qb6 $11 {The best, to repeat to moves.} (11... Be7 $5 {You can also play on.} 12. O-O O-O 13. g4 Nh4 {New unclear position.} 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. g5 Qd8 16. f4 f6 $13 {[%eval 0,0] for the engine, if you are ready for an adventure, this is a good way. But personally, I prefer to repeat the moves.})) 7... Bd7 $5 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Rb1d2,Gd4c3] Black's strategy is very simple. We are waiting for Nbd2, only then we are going to take on c3 (since the knight cannot recapture).} (7... dxc3 $6 {We don't go for this, we will play positionally instead.} 8. Nxc3 $13 {[%csl Gc3] The knight on c3 stays well, position is very unclear.}) 8. Re1 {White usually starts with this, still hoping for dxc3-Nxc3.} (8. Nbd2 $6 {Whenever this move happens:} dxc3 $1 {[%csl Gb1,Rd2][%cal Gb1c3] We are very happy to take.} 9. bxc3 Nge7 10. Nb3 Ng6 11. Re1 {Transposing to the main line.}) 8... Nge7 {Finish development.} 9. h4 $1 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Re7g6,Gh4h5] The best move for White, prophylaxis against Ng6 (which is met with h5).} (9. a3 $6 {This move is not useful.} Ng6 10. h4 Be7 11. h5 Nh4 $15 {Black has a good position of course, pawn up.}) (9. Nbd2 {We follow the rule:} dxc3 $1 {And White is forced to capture with the pawn.} 10. bxc3 Ng6 {[%csl Re5] To immediately pressure the e5 pawn.} 11. Nb3 $1 {Best move.} Qc7 12. Qe2 {Necessary to defend e5.} Be7 13. Nbd4 {There are some games, but not high level ones:} O-O {Black is absolutely fine, we can check a sample line.} 14. Rb1 f5 $5 {Many moves are possible, I like this plan.} 15. exf6 Rxf6 16. Bxg6 Rxg6 17. Nxc6 Bxc6 18. Ne5 {This is maximum what White can achieve, but it's not problematic, of course.} Rf6 19. Bg5 Rff8 20. Nxc6 Bxg5 21. Qxe6+ Kh8 22. Ne5 Rad8 $11 {Just equal position.}) 9... a6 {I like this useful move the most.} (9... Rc8 {I don't recommend this move, because in the critical line:} 10. Nbd2 dxc3 11. bxc3 Ng6 12. h5 Bc5 {[%csl Rc8] With a pawn on a6, this is good, but with the rook on c8, this is lost!} 13. Rb1 $1 Bxf2+ 14. Kf1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Rb6a7] And no squares for the queen.} Qc5 15. Rb5 $18 {Game over.}) (9... h6 {I don't recommend this move, because my positional idea is to meet h5 with g6, which is not possible here.} 10. h5 $13 {[%cal Rg7g6] g6 is just positional disaster now.}) 10. h5 {The most common continuation.} (10. a3 $6 {This is too slow.} dxc3 {We can also take on c3, because Black stopped the Nb5 ideas after} (10... Rc8 $5 {is possible.}) 11. Nxc3 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 $15 {More than fine for Black.}) (10. Nbd2 {is again met with} dxc3 $1 {Key positional idea.} 11. bxc3 Ng6 12. Nb3 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gh4h5,Gf8c5,Gg6f4] Main move, stopping both ideas.} (12. h5 $6 {fails tactically:} Bc5 $1 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Rc5f2] Good intermezzo.} 13. Rb1 Bxf2+ 14. Kf1 Qa7 $1 {[%csl Ba6,Ga7] All thanks to the move a6.} 15. Nb3 {Still, engine evaluates this as only -0.50.} Bxe1 {Black is not winning, but is better.} 16. Qxe1 Nge7 17. Be3 d4 $5 {[%cal Gd7c6] To have the diagonal open for the bishop in future.} 18. Nbxd4 Qb8 $15 {Just position, no problem for Black.}) 12... Qc7 $1 {[%csl Re5] Important tempo, to target the e5 pawn.} 13. Qe2 f6 $3 {Key move of this line.} (13... Be7 $6 {looks very logical, but it leads to positional advantage for White!} 14. h5 $1 Nh4 15. Nxh4 Bxh4 16. h6 $1 {Strong push.} g6 17. Ba3 {The dark squares are terribly weak.} Be7 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Rab1 $14 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Re8g8] More than compensation, +0.40 for White.}) 14. exf6 gxf6 {There are 15 games here, the position is a total fight:} 15. c4 (15. Rb1 $5 {Tricky, White has a trap in the position ready.} Bd6 {Useful move.} (15... O-O-O $2 {Don't fall for it.} 16. Bxa6 $1 $40 {[%csl Rc8] And Black cannot recapture on a6.}) 16. Nbd4 e5 17. Nf5 Bc5 $13 {This is how the game Papp-Divya, Grenke 2024 continued, in the end Black won, so we can assume that it is more dangerous for White than for Black. For the engine, it's 0.00.}) 15... O-O-O $1 $13 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gg6f4,Gc8b8,Gf8d6] We can stop here, it's 0.00 for the engine, Black has a lot of ideas and useful moves.}) 10... g6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] This is why I chose 9...a6 instead of 9...h6.} 11. Nbd2 {The best move.} (11. h6 $2 {was played in the game Mamedov-Markoya.} Ng8 $1 {[%csl Gg8,Rh6][%cal Cg8h6] The pawn is just lost.} 12. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 $19 {[%csl Rh6] Improvement over the game, the pawn on h6 is not running anywhere.}) 11... gxh5 $1 {We change concepts, and actually win the second pawn.} (11... dxc3 $6 {[%csl Rg6] The only moment where we don't follow the rule, because with the pawn on g6, the dynamic changes a bit.} 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. c4 $36 {The dark squares are weak, it's quite unpleasant to play with Black.}) 12. Nb3 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb3d4] The best move, forcing us to take on c3.} (12. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1g3] Logical move, to continue with Ng3, but it is met with} h4 $1 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Rf1g3] Kamikaze pawn, it stops Ng3 and it also deflects the f3 knight.} 13. Nxh4 Ng6 $1 {Extra tempo.} 14. Nf3 dxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7 {[%csl Re5] The e5 pawn drops.} 16. Ng3 O-O-O $15 {And take on e5 next.} (16... Ncxe5 $5 {This is also possible of course.})) 12... dxc3 {Forced.} 13. bxc3 Ng6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Rb6c7] We continue the plan to put pressure on e5, typical idea.} 14. Rb1 (14. Nbd4 {will lead to the same.} Qc7 15. Rb1 {see under 14.Rb1.}) 14... Qc7 15. Nbd4 {The key position of the chapter, but good news is that only 6 games happened here, and Black has more than one good continuation:} Rg8 $5 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ga8c8] I like this move the most, it has been played only in 1 game. Frankly, I don't see a constructive plan for White, while Black has a lot of useful moves.} (15... Bg7 {The most common line.} 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 (16... Qxc6 17. Ba3) 17. Nd4 $1 {The best move.} (17. Ba3 {was played in Ganguly-Cheng, 2022.} O-O-O $1 $146 {Black is fine here.}) 17... Bd7 {Sample line:} 18. Rb3 Ba4 19. Rxb7 Qxb7 20. Qxa4+ Qd7 21. Bb5 axb5 22. Qxa8+ Qd8 $11 {Engine evalution is equal.}) (15... h4 $5 {deserves attention.}) 16. Nxc6 {The best for the engine, to release the pressure on the e5 pawn.} (16. c4 $2 {is just bad.} dxc4 $19 {[%cal Rd3c4] And Bxc4 is not possible.}) (16. Be3 {Logical move, against Bc5.} Rc8 $15 {[%csl Re5] Good move. e5 pawn shall drop sooner or later.} (16... Bc5 $2 {Don't fall for the trap!} 17. Nxe6 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7] Small tactic.})) 16... Bxc6 $5 {Safer move, in my opinion.} (16... Qxc6 {is one option, but you have to reckon with the move 17.c4.} 17. c4 $5 {is White's idea.} (17. Nd4 Qxc3) 17... dxc4 18. Be4 Qa4 {White can take on b7 with equality, or} 19. Bc2 $5 Qa5 (19... Qc6 $11) 20. Rxb7 O-O-O 21. Bd2 Qxa2 $13 {Interesting position, who knows what is going on here.}) 17. Nd4 Bd7 {[%csl Gd7] To keep the bishop.} 18. Bd2 {We can follow the first line of engine:} Nxe5 19. Bf4 Bd6 20. Qxh5 Nf3+ $1 {Small tactical motif.} 21. Qxf3 Bxf4 22. c4 Kf8 $5 {If you play this human move, it's also 0.00.} (22... Bd2 $5 {is computer best, but very tough to understand.}) 23. cxd5 exd5 24. Bf5 {The professional engine move.} (24. Qxd5 $6 {Taking is too risky.} Rd8 25. Qf3 Bc8 $36 {[%csl Gf8,Rg1][%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black's king on f8 is at least not weaker than the g1 king.}) 24... Be5 25. Ne6+ $5 {The last drop of gasoline on the fire.} (25. Bxd7 Bxd4 $11 {Equal position, no problem.}) 25... fxe6 26. Bxe6+ Kg7 27. Qf7+ Kh8 {And it all goes down to an equal endgame, as always.} 28. Qxd7 Qxd7 29. Bxd7 Bc3 $11 {[%cal Gd5d4] We went quite deep, but I think for the 6.Bd3 line this is a good amount of knowledge to have and especially we understood well the positional details of this gambit. Everywhere, we have a position for 3 results, usually Black is up in material, so there is nothing for you to be scared about when facing this rare gambit.} *

