{[%evp 0,60,30,21,37,28,36,13,13,2,7,14,1,-8,-19,-55,-13,-1,-18,-11,1,-15,-33,-28,-25,-25,-30,-23,-19,-17,-10,-13,8,6,32,53,41,70,53,48,48,57,47,40,36,6,0,31,96,84,81,81,116,116,104,114,116,143,143,91,121,114,120]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Be2 {The topic of this chapter. Not a dangerous line, but Black needs to decide what to do.} Nh6 $5 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc5d4,Rc3d4,Rb1c3] This is my recommendation. Same idea as in the main line, but we delay cxd4 cxd4 so that White's knight cannot develop to c3.} (6... Bd7 {The second main line.} 7. O-O cxd4 8. cxd4 Nge7 9. Nc3 {Engine suggests White is slightly better after the line:} Nf5 10. Na4 Qa5 11. b3 b5 12. Nc5 Nfxd4 13. Nxd7 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Kxd7 15. Ng5 $14 {King in the center, +0.50 evaluation, I don't feel comfortable with Black.}) (6... cxd4 {is the main line.} 7. cxd4 Nh6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gh6f5] Black plans to put maximum pressure on d4 pawn.} (7... Nge7 $6 {allows White to develop.} 8. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rf8][%cal Rf8a3] The bishop cannot capture anymore.} Nf5 9. Nc2 $14 {White is slightly better, Black is a bit passive.}) 8. Bxh6 {The critical move.} (8. Nc3 {The second minus is that White can force a draw by repetition.} Nf5 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 $11 {[%cal Ga5b6] Qb6 is absolutely necessary, second best move is +0.60 for White already.}) 8... Qxb2 {Main theory, and here I don't like 2 things:} (8... gxh6 {is not equalizing.} 9. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3] The knight gets this nice square to develop.} Qxb2 (9... Bg7 {Normal moves don't help Black, since White has easy play thanks to the knight being on c3.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Na4 Qa5 12. a3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4] Simple plan, evaluation is +1 already.}) 10. Nb5 Qb4+ 11. Kf1 $14 {This is advantage for White.}) 9. Nc3 $5 {Rare move, but poses big questions.} (9. Nbd2 {I am sure that with some work, Black can equalize, but Black needs to remember concrete moves:} gxh6 10. O-O Nxd4 $5 {Sample line:} (10... Bd7 $11 {The best move, but White has really a lot of ideas, and Black needs to be very careful.}) 11. Rb1 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 Qa3 13. Nd4 a6 14. Rfd1 $132 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gd2f1,Gf1g3,Gg3h5] White can hope to put a knight to h5 one day, it can be unpleasant.}) 9... Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qa3 11. h4 $36 {[%cal Gh1h3,Ge1f1] I know engine shows 0.00, but it could be difficult to play from the Black side, White has easy play.}) 7. Bxh6 {Critical capture to ruin the structure.} (7. O-O {Possible move.} cxd4 8. Bxh6 $1 {Only move.} (8. cxd4 $2 {Automatic move, but probably just losing.} Nf5 $1 $19 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4][%cal Rc1e3,Rb6b2] White cannot defend the d4 pawn, resigning is understandable.}) 8... dxc3 $1 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc3b2] Strong intermezzo.} (8... gxh6 $6 9. cxd4 Qxb2 10. Nbd2 $36 {And we transpose to the line that I don't like for Black.}) 9. Nxc3 gxh6 {[%csl Rb2,Gd5] Black is pawn up now, d4 is more important than b2 pawn.} 10. Na4 Qb4 $132 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gb4e7,Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Black has very easy moves, it is White who has to work hard to prove compensation.}) (7. Na3 $6 {is not good, because the bishop on f8 isn't blocked.} cxd4 8. cxd4 Bxa3 $1 {Typical idea.} 9. bxa3 Nf5 {Dream scenario for Black, all pieces are active.} 10. Be3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Bd7 $15 {Very comfortable endgame, probably slightly better for Black.}) (7. b3 $2 {is often played, but of course, a very slow move.} cxd4 8. O-O {The best, and White is only slightly worse after} (8. cxd4 {The main line, but it fails to} Bb4+ $1 {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Rb4e1] Very annoying intermezzo.} (8... Nf5 $6 {is not precise.} 9. Bb2 $11 {Black is fine, but also White has a game.}) 9. Kf1 {The only move.} O-O $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Gf7f6] Strong improvement, and only 7 games compared to 150 games in 9...Nf5.} (9... Nf5 $6 {is an automatic move, but not good.} 10. Bb2 $132 {Playable.}) 10. Bxh6 gxh6 {[%cal Gf7f6] f6 next, and the evaluation is more than -1.} 11. a3 Be7 12. Nc3 f6 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Re5,Rf1] White's center evaporates, and with that also king safety.}) 8... dxc3 9. Nxc3 Bd7 $15 {No games, and White doesn't have full compensation.}) 7... gxh6 {[%cal Rb1c3] But you see, compared to the main line, no Nc3 is possible, so this makes it an improved version for Black.} 8. Qd2 {Only good move, but logical one.} Bg7 9. O-O {Necessary move.} (9. Na3 {is the same.} O-O 10. O-O {White cannot play without short castle, check the main line.}) 9... O-O {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8d7] Black has an easy plan: f7-f6.} 10. Na3 {White plays this automatic move, 176 games out of 180.} cxd4 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Gc3][%cal Rb1a3,Gb1c3] Good moment to take, and good understanding, because White's knight cannot develop to c3 anymore.} 11. cxd4 f6 $5 {This is always necessary move for Black, so better to do it immediately.} 12. exf6 Rxf6 {The key position of this chapter.} 13. Nc2 {White improves the knight, no other logical moves. Be careful with Black now!} a5 $1 {[%csl Bc6,Ye5][%cal Rb2b4,Bc6e5] The most precise move, important to stop White's key strategical idea.} (13... Bd7 $6 {is almost an automatic move, but it's a small mistake!} 14. b4 $1 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gb4b5,Rc6e7,Gf3e5] Important idea for White, the plan is b5-Ne5, securing a small advantage.} a6 {Logical, to stop b5, but not for long.} (14... Raf8 {Human move.} 15. b5 Ne7 (15... Na5 16. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ga2,Ra7] With a pawn on a2, and Black's pawn on a7, this is of course different music.}) 16. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Ge5] White is better here, with easy play next.}) 15. a4 Be8 16. b5 Na5 17. Rab1 {And visually and objectively, White has the initiative on the queenside.} axb5 18. Ne3 $14 {Not the end of the world, but slightly worse for Black.}) 14. Rab1 $5 {This move deserves attention. Black has another deep move.} (14. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2b5] Logical move as well, White highlights the downside of our pawn being on a5.} Bd7 15. Bb5 {[%csl Ga8] Another key moment, and good exercise for your positional understanding: where does the a8 rook belong?} Be8 $1 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Rb2b4] It was a trick question, the rook is very good where it stays right now, since it is prophylactic against White's queenside play.} (15... Raf8 $6 {is logical automatic move, the rook belongs on a semi-open file, right?} 16. Bxc6 $1 {Wrong! The knight will anyways leave f3, and both rooks are useless.} bxc6 17. Ne5 Be8 18. b4 $14 {[%csl Ga8,Rf8] Advantage for White, the rook from f8 belongs back to a8.}) 16. Rae1 {Standard move.} (16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. b4 {[%csl Ga8] Compared to the critical line after Raf8, here it is a much better version for Black.} axb4 18. Qxb4 {A nice line:} Qxb4 19. Nxb4 Rxf3 $1 {Typical exchange sacrifice.} 20. gxf3 Bxd4 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5] Very good winning chances for Black.}) 16... Bg6 17. Ne5 {was played in the game Languidey-Contin, 2024.} Nxe5 18. dxe5 Rf5 19. Bd3 {Black took on b2, sacrificing the exchange, not necessary.} Rxe5 $1 $146 {was the best, very deep move.} 20. Rxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxg6 hxg6 22. Qxh6 {It looks interesting for White, but for one move only!} Kf7 $3 $15 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Ga8h8,Gh6h7,Ge5g7] The king is mega safe on f7, Rh8 is coming next, the bishop is fantastic.}) (14. a3 {The most logical move, White insists on b2-b4.} Bd7 $1 {Good developing move, the inclusion of a3-a5 was in Black's favor, and the reason for that is} (14... a4 $6 {seems like the most logical, and it was also played in the game Timman-Vaganian, but not a precise move:} 15. Nb4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Rc6,Ge5][%cal Gf3e5] Black loses control of the e5 square, and White has a positional advantage.}) 15. b4 a4 $1 {[%csl Ga4] The key positional idea. b5 now will be too commiting for White, since the a4 pawn controls the b3 square, and also fixes the a3 weakness.} 16. Bd3 {White has to make just useful improving moves now, we can check how the game can continue:} (16. b5 $2 {[%csl Rb5] Positional mistake.} Na5 $36 {[%csl Ra3,Ga4,Gb3][%cal Ga5b3] Black has the b3 square, compared to 13...Bd7 line, and also a3 pawn is weak in any endgame.}) 16... Kh8 {Useful prophlyactic move.} 17. Rae1 Rc8 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8h5] Absolutely good position for Black, no problem.} 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Rff8 $11 {[%csl Ra3,Ga4][%cal Gc8c7,Gf8c8,Gd7e8,Ge8g6] 0.00 evaluation, Black has standard moves, it's a fight for 3 results, and the a4 pawn guarantees us long-term positional trumps.}) (14. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3g4] Standard move, with idea of Ng4-e5.} h5 $1 {Good moment to stop it.} 15. Rad1 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6,Gg8h8] Just equal position, Black is doing fine.}) 14... Rf8 $3 {[%csl Ga8,Rb1,Gb7,Gc8,Rd4][%cal Gc8b7] Deep move, we have already seen after 14.a4 that the rook was useful on its initial square, but here the bishop on c8 does a very good job against White's rook on b1, since it keeps b7 defended.} (14... Bd7 $6 {Of course, nothing terrible will happen, but White gets the small initiative and the play they are looking for:} 15. b4 $1 axb4 16. Nxb4 $36 {[%csl Rb7,Rd7] Some problems with the b7 pawn.}) 15. Rfd1 {[%csl Cd4][%cal Gd2d4,Cb2b4] Logical continuation, to protect d4 and play b4 next.} (15. b4 $2 {is not possible anymore.} axb4 16. Nxb4 Nxd4 $1 $17 {Another point of 14...Rf8.}) 15... Kh8 {Useful move.} 16. b4 e5 $1 {Time for dynamic chess.} 17. dxe5 Nxe5 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Rd2d5,Gc8e6] And you see how the previous move was useful for us.} 18. bxa5 {Critical line.} (18. Nxe5 {Don't get lured into the trap!} Bxe5 (18... Qxf2+ $4 {Huge mistake.} 19. Kh1 Bxe5 20. Rf1 $1 $18 {[%csl Gf1,Rf8] This is White's trap.}) 19. Ne3 axb4 $11 {[%csl Ca2,Gb7,Gc8,Ge5,Cf2,Gh6,Gh7][%cal Ge5g7] 0.00 position, equal material, very strange structure, but White has some targets in the position.}) 18... Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Qxa5 20. Rb4 {The best engine move.} (20. Qxa5 {The endgame can become unpleasant for White!} Rxa5 21. Bxd5 Bf5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc2e3] The best is Ne3 to sacrifice the exchange and hold the endgame.}) 20... d4 $1 {To disrupt the coordination.} 21. Nxd4 Qxa2 22. Qxa2 Rxa2 {The endgame is of course equal, Black has a lot of activity.} 23. Nb5 Ra1 24. Rxa1 Bxa1 25. Nd6 {This is how the ''professional line'' continues} Be5 26. Nxc8 Rxc8 27. g3 Rc1+ 28. Kg2 Rc2 29. Bxb7 Rb2 30. Rxb2 Bxb2 $11 {Equal drawn endgame, of course, if White will play like an engine, any line will end up this way, but we have done a good way to solve the opening problems and have chances to overtake the initiative as well. Please recheck the positional moments and if you understand better the position, you are going to have an interesting battle, in your own games!} *

