{[%evp 0,42,25,24,37,33,32,9,-9,10,11,-10,7,-23,-23,16,16,16,5,-13,-3,10,13,7,7,-39,-35,-24,-29,-22,18,19,5,-11,-4,10,14,14,14,20,32,32,32,25,32]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Bd7 7. b4 (7. Be2 {Usually transposes in the mainline.} Nh6 {[%csl Gh6] our typical move.} 8. b4 (8. O-O $6 cxd4 9. cxd4 $2 Nf5 $17 {[%csl Rd4] Typical problems with the d4 pawn.}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 {White's most common continuation, by far.} (9. Bxh6 {independent line, and Black has a very good solution to it, but it's important to remember it.} gxh6 10. cxd4 Rg8 $1 {[%cal Gg8g2] Rxg2 is a threat.} 11. O-O Rg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4,Gg4][%cal Gg4d4] key idea, with pressure against d4.} 12. h3 Rf4 13. g3 Rxf3 $1 {[%csl Bf3] third key move to remember.} 14. Bxf3 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nxd4 16. Bh5 Bg7 17. f4 Ke7 $44 {[%cal Gf7f6] f6 next, and Black has full compensation and easy play.}) (9. O-O $5 {Extremely rare, only three games played by people without rating, but it's a possible move.} dxc3 (9... Nf5 10. Bd3 $1 $146) 10. Nxc3 Nf5 $13 {[%eval 0,0] is the engine's evaluation. White has compensation, but no more. It's an interesting new position that requires some practical test.}) 9... Nf5 10. Bb2 Rc8 {Transposes in the mainline of this chapter.}) 7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc1,Gd4][%cal Gc6d4]} 9. Be2 {This move is not so critical, but by analyzing it, we can learn some typical ideas of the position.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black's typical idea is Nf5-Be7-00. But this plan works only in theory; in practice, it's very rare that we will execute it because something always happens in between.} (9... Nxd4 $5 {This exchange sacrifice deserves attention because after} 10. Nxd4 Rxc1 11. Qxc1 Qxd4 12. Qc3 Qxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Ne7 $44 {Black has full compensation. For example:} 14. Rc1 (14. O-O Nc6 15. f4 g5 16. g3 h5 $44) 14... Nc6 15. Nb5 Nxe5 16. Rc7 (16. Nxa7 Kd8 $11) 16... a6 17. Nd4 Nc6 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. O-O Kd8 20. Rxf7 Ke8 21. Rf3 Bd6 $44) 10. O-O (10. Bb2 Nf5 11. g4 $6 (11. O-O {trans in 10.00.}) 11... Nfe7 $1 {[%csl Rg4] White's pawn on g4 is misplaced because we have now h5 ideas.} 12. Nc3 Ng6 13. Qd2 h5 14. g5 Nce7 $5 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5] Nf5 next, and Black is already better.}) 10... Nf5 {White can defend the d4 pawn by placing the bishop on e3 or on b2.} 11. Bb2 (11. Be3 {Black has now a very simple continuation:} Nxe3 12. fxe3 Ne7 {[%cal Gd7b5] our idea is Bb5.} 13. Qd2 {[%csl Yc3][%cal Gb1c3,Yd2c3] White supports Nc3.} Ng6 (13... Bb5 $2 {not good now because of} 14. Bxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nc3 Qd7 16. e4 $16) 14. Nc3 Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Yf7f6,Ya7a5] 00 next, and then we can play for f6 or a5.}) 11... Be7 (11... Na5 $6 {This is a typical idea for Black in these positions, but right now, it is premature.} 12. Nbd2 $1 Nc4 13. Nxc4 dxc4 14. Rc1 $16 {and Black faces concrete problems, mainly because he still needs two tempi to castle.}) 12. Qd2 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gf1d1] White's most common continuation. The idea is to protect the d4 pawn by playing Rd1, and then develop the knight on c3.} (12. Kh1 {After this waiting useful move,} Na5 {becomes possible, because the inclusion of Be7-Kh1 favors Black:} 13. Nbd2 Nc4 14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. Rc1 Qa6 16. d5 exd5 17. Qxd5 b5 $15 {[%csl Ge7] Of course, it's a big difference to have the bishop on e7 or on f8.}) (12. g4 Nh4 13. Nxh4 Bxh4 14. Qd3 {[%cal Gb1d2] White prepares Nd2, which was not possible immediately due to the hanging pawn on d4.} f6 $1 (14... O-O {Would be slow, because of:} 15. Nd2 f6 16. Nf3 {Black is still fine after Bg5, but no need to go for these complications.}) 15. Nd2 fxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17. Nf3 Be7 $36 {[%csl Rg4] Black's position is preferable, at least because the pawn on g4 is misplaced.}) (12. Qd3 {Was played by Caruana.} Na5 $1 13. Nbd2 Nc4 14. Nxc4 dxc4 15. Qd2 {This is a better move than Qc3 because after Rc1, White will threaten the c4 pawn for real.} (15. Qc3 $6 {Caruana played Qc3, but maybe Qd2 was better.} O-O 16. Nd2 Qd8 $1 $15 {[%cal Gd7c6] Bc6 next, and Black is slightly better.}) 15... Qd8 $5 (15... O-O 16. Rac1 $14) 16. g4 (16. Rac1 b5 17. d5 exd5 18. Qxd5 Bc6 $15) 16... Nh4 17. Nxh4 Bxh4 18. f4 {typical idea.} O-O 19. Bf3 (19. f5 $2 f6 $1 $17) (19. g5 $6 h6 $1 20. gxh6 gxh6 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gg8h8,Gf8g8] Kh8-Rg8 next.}) 19... Bc6 20. Bxc6 Rxc6 21. Bc3 f5 $36 {If White plays g5, we can play h6 once again. I cannot say that Black has an advantage, but it is for sure more pleasant to play the position from the Black side.}) (12. Bd3 $5 {A concrete move tried by Gavrilescu.} Ncxd4 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 14. Qg4 {This is White's idea.} Nb3 $1 $146 {[%csl Bb3]} (14... Nf5 $6 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Qxg7 Rf8 17. Nc3 Qg6 18. Qxg6 fxg6 19. Nxd5 $14 {This endgame may be a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 15. Qxg7 (15. Ra2 $2 g6 $17) 15... Rf8 16. Ra2 h5 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gd7b5,Ya7a5] We can continue with h4, then Bb5 or a5. The position is balanced.}) 12... h5 $1 13. Bc3 $5 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gc3a5] White's idea is b5-Ba5.} (13. Rc1 $5 g5 14. Nxg5 Ncxd4 15. Rxc8+ Bxc8 16. Nf3 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 Bd7 $11 {Balanced position.}) (13. Rd1 $2 {White's idea, but a mistake!} g5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh8g8,Ge7g5] We can continue with g4 and then eventually Rg8-Bg5.}) 13... a6 $1 {[%cal Yg7g5] We must play this prophylactic move. Our idea is now g5.} 14. Bd3 g5 15. Bxf5 g4 $1 (15... exf5 {also possible, but a bit strange.} 16. Nxg5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Ne7 $13 {Engine thinks that it's equal.}) 16. Be4 $3 {very strong positional move. White gives back the material on his terms.} (16. Bxg4 hxg4 17. Ne1 f5 $1 $36 {[%cal Ge8f7] Kf7 next, and we have a huge initiative on the 'h' file.}) 16... dxe4 17. Ng5 Bxg5 18. Qxg5 Nxd4 19. Qe3 Nf3+ $1 20. gxf3 Qxe3 21. fxe3 gxf3 $44 {Very interesting position; Black has full compensation for the sacrificed piece.} *

