{[%evp 0,48,35,35,35,22,24,11,11,10,10,10,-12,-1,11,11,11,11,2,2,9,17,20,18,27,25,38,38,36,5,42,47,31,32,32,35,35,17,27,12,12,-8,8,1,9,3,11,-1,-1,-1,0]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Bd7 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 9. Be3 {Against Be3, we lose our Na5 ideas, but we can play for Nh6-Ng4, targeting White's bishop on e3.} Nh6 10. Bd3 {White prevents Nf5.} (10. Bxh6 $2 {Bad move.} gxh6 11. Be2 Rg8 $1 $146 {Strong move.} 12. Nc3 {Only move for White.} (12. O-O Rg4 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) 12... Rxg2 13. Na4 Qd8 $15 {Black is better also here.}) (10. Nbd2 {Not interesting.} Nf5 11. Bd3 Nd8 $1 {[%cal Gd7b5] Nice positional idea.} 12. O-O Nxe3 13. fxe3 Rc3 14. Qe2 Rxd3 15. Qxd3 Bb5 $11 {Equal position.}) 10... Ng4 $1 {The correct way to attack e3.} (10... Nf5 $2 {Logical, but not good! Be careful.} 11. Bxf5 exf5 12. O-O Nd8 {Same idea, but White has} 13. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3] Very strong move.} Bb5 14. Re1 Ne6 15. Nc3 Qc6 16. Rc1 $14 {Position is quite unpleasant for Black.}) 11. O-O {The most played by far.} (11. Nbd2 $5 {I think this is a more interesting direction for White, it has been played in the crucial game: Sindarov-Pragg, Olympiad 2024. The coach of Uzbekistan team in that event was Vladimir Kramnik, so I beleive it is his idea, because it is very deep and in his style!} Be7 12. Qe2 Nxe3 13. fxe3 f5 $1 $146 {[%csl Re1,Re2] This is a good antidote, but be careful not to do it against the 11.0-0 variation!} (13... Nb8 {Pragg went for the natural plan, as in the main line.} 14. b5 $1 {[%csl Gb5,Rb8] This is White's idea!} (14. O-O a6 {Transposes to 11.0-0.}) 14... Bxa3 {Black wins a pawn, but it was all preparation:} 15. O-O Be7 16. Rfb1 O-O 17. g4 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rb8][%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4] Incredible idea, Black's pieces are stuck, so White starts a very fast attack!} Rc3 18. g5 Rfc8 19. h4 Be8 {Another instructive moment:} 20. Nh2 $1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh2g4] To improve the knight, Sindarov still didn't spend any time on the clock.} Nd7 21. Ng4 Kh8 22. Kh1 {I tried to analyze this position for Black, but it's extremely dangerous.} Qd8 $5 $146 {Improvement over the game.} (22... Nf8 {was Pragg's move.} 23. Nf3 $14 {In the end, it was a draw, but White has advantage here.}) 23. Rg1 Ra3 $1 {Only move.} 24. Rxa3 Bxa3 25. Nf6 Rc1 $1 {To trade the last pair of rooks.} 26. Rxc1 Bxc1 27. Nxh7 f5 $3 28. gxf6 gxf6 29. exf6 Nxf6 30. Ng5 $11 {Okay, engine says it is equal, but it is only a sample line, White had many other deviations, from human perspective it is very tough for Black to defend so precise, when all pieces are on the queenside, and White just pushes forward.}) 14. exf6 (14. Nb3 {is what engine recommends.} a5 $1 {Good move.} 15. b5 Nd8 16. a4 {Necessary otherwise, Black will play a4.} O-O 17. O-O Nf7 $11 {[%cal Gb6a7,Gb7b6,Gc8c3,Gf8c8] In the start engine showed +0.20, now it dropped to 0.00, it understood that Black's play is natural and that the counterplay is enough.}) 14... Bxf6 15. Nb3 O-O 16. Nc5 (16. O-O e5 $1 {Nice move, Black has counterplay.} 17. Nc5 Bg4 $132) 16... Qc7 17. Rc1 {White goes for the critical line, but here Black is in time:} b6 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Ba6 Rc7 20. Qc2 {The same position with castle included is just lost for Black, here it is another story:} (20. O-O Qd6 21. Qc2 Rff7 $1 $11 {Black unpins.}) 20... Rf7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c7] Strong move to overprotect c7.} 21. Bb5 $2 Nxd4 $1 $19 {[%csl Rc2,Re1][%cal Gd4c2,Rd4f3] This is the tactical trick.}) 11... Be7 {Better way to start.} (11... Nxe3 {Possible, but a bit early.} 12. fxe3 Be7 13. Qe1 $5 {is one extra option you need to deal with.}) 12. Nbd2 {The logical move.} (12. Qe1 $6 {Here Black has a nice reaction:} g5 $3 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Rg4e3,Gg5g4] Fantastic idea, to create threats against the f3 knight.} 13. h3 {Necessary move.} (13. Bxg5 $4 {Extremely bad.} Bxg5 14. Nxg5 Qxd4 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rd3] Double attack, winning position simply.}) 13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4] To continue the kingside pressure.} 15. Qg3 Nd8 $5 {More precise for the engine.} (15... Rg8 $5 {is good enough, human move.}) 16. Nxg5 Rg8 17. h4 Bb5 $36 {Initiative for Black.}) (12. Qd2 {Also a rare move.} Nxe3 13. fxe3 (13. Qxe3 $2 {Bad, because of the typical idea} g5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re3,Rf3] White is worse.}) 13... O-O {Solid line:} (13... g5 $5 {also possible, if you want to be creative.}) 14. Nc3 f6 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Rac1 Ne7 $11 {[%csl Ra4,Gd7][%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6,Ge8h5,Rc3a4] Typical French position.}) 12... Nxe3 {Good moment to capture.} 13. fxe3 {Be careful, Black has an important move:} Nb8 $1 {[%csl Bb8][%cal Gd7b5] Key starting move, the positional idea is Bb5.} (13... O-O $6 {Natural move, but Black doesn't have time for it.} 14. Nb3 Nb8 {[%cal Gd7b5] With idea Bb5.} 15. Qe2 a6 16. Nc5 Bb5 {Black achieves it, but White is in control:} 17. Bxb5 axb5 18. Rac1 Qc6 {This is how the game Vitiugov-Berkes, World Cup 2023 continued.} 19. e4 $1 $146 {Good improvement.} dxe4 20. Nxe4 Qxc1 21. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 22. Kf2 $14 {Black can hold this endgame maybe, but it's quite unpleasant.}) (13... f5 $2 {Be careful when you do this, here it is a bad time!} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Nb3 {[%csl Gb3,Re2] Much more useful move than Qe2.} O-O 16. Nc5 Qc7 17. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c8] Black is just busted.} b6 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. Ba6 Rc7 20. Qc2 $18 {[%cal Ga6b5] Bb5 next and Black can resign.}) 14. Qe2 {Critical move against Bb5.} (14. Nb3 {If White allows us, Black is fine:} Bb5 15. Nc5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 O-O 17. Rac1 Qc6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7] Nd7 next, Black is okay.} 18. a4 $6 {was played in the game Peng-Yu, Black had the opportunity to overtake the initiative.} Na6 $3 $146 {Strong idea.} 19. Nxa6 Qxc1 20. Rxc1 Rxc1+ {This endgame is totally different compared to the Vitiugov-Berkes game.} 21. Kf2 bxa6 22. Qxa6 Bxb4 23. Qxa7 Rfc8 $36 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4,Gc1,Gc8,Rf3] It is Black of course who is playing for a win, very active pieces and the knight on f3 is out of the game.}) (14. b5 $2 {This is a typical blunder for this structure:} Rc3 $1 15. Qe2 Rxd3 $1 {And Black wins a pawn.} 16. Qxd3 Bxb5 $17 {[%csl Rd3,Rf1][%cal Gb5f1]}) 14... a6 $5 {I think this is more human, and it's easier to play and understand.} (14... Rc3 $5 {[%cal Rc3d3] Possible move with idea of Rxd3-Bb5.} 15. Rfb1 $5 {Prophylactic move.} a6 16. Nb3 Bb5 17. Bxb5+ Qxb5 {The endgame is equal, only if Black is extremely precise:} 18. Qd2 Qd3 19. Qxd3 Rxd3 20. Nc5 Rxe3 21. Nxb7 Nc6 22. Nc5 Bxc5 23. bxc5 O-O 24. Rb6 Rc8 $1 {Only move.} 25. Rxa6 g5 $1 {Only way, to get counterplay.} 26. h3 h5 $11 {But at maximum Black is just playing for a draw.}) 15. Nb3 $5 {[%cal Ga1c1,Ra6a5] The most serious try, the idea is to fight for c-line, without allowing a5 counterplay.} (15. h4 Bb5 $11 {Engine says it is +0.01, but obviously we cannot be scared of this.}) (15. e4 {Logical try.} Rc3 $1 $146 {Now this is great.} 16. exd5 (16. Rfb1 {In the same variation, e4 will be a liability.} O-O 17. Nb3 dxe4 $1 {Our bishop will be active, and of course, evaluation changes.} 18. Qxe4 g6 19. Nc5 Bc6 $36 {[%csl Gc6] Black is slightly better.}) 16... exd5 17. Rfc1 (17. Rfb1 {The difference now, is that Black can play on the kingside.} O-O 18. Nb3 Qh6 $1 19. Nc5 Bg4 $1 $40 {[%csl Gg4,Gh6][%cal Ge6d5,Re4d5] That's why exd5 is positionally dubious decision.}) 17... Rxc1+ 18. Rxc1 a5 $1 $11 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4] Once White's rook leaves the a-file, this push becomes a lot stronger.}) (15. Rac1 {Harmless try.} Rxc1 16. Rxc1 a5 $11 {Black is fine, if not preferable.}) 15... Bb5 16. Nc5 {was played in Abdusattorov-Grischuk, 2024.} (16. Bxb5+ {was played in the game Prathamesh-Jeremic.} Qxb5 17. Qxb5+ axb5 {The endgame is equal, with natural moves:} 18. Rfc1 Rxc1+ 19. Rxc1 Kd7 20. Nc5+ Bxc5 {Good moment to take.} 21. bxc5 (21. Rxc5 b6 $3 {[%cal Rc5b5] is the point, the b5 pawn is immune.} 22. Rxb5 $4 Kc6 $19 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ra3a4,Gb8a6,Ga6c7] White is lost.}) 21... h6 $5 {[%cal Rf3g5] Useful move against Ng5.} 22. Rb1 Kc6 $11 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb8d7,Gh8a8] Good endgame, actually it can become tricky for White to defend a3 if not careful.}) 16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 O-O {[%cal Gb6a7,Gb7b6] Grischuk showed a model plan:} 18. Rab1 Qa7 $1 {[%cal Gb7b6] Grischuk is fighting for more.} (18... Qc6 {This equalizes, but White has some ideas.} 19. a4 {[%cal Gb4b5]} b6 20. b5 Qa8 21. Nxa6 Rc4 $11 {Maximum equality for Black.}) 19. Rfc1 b6 20. Na4 {We can improve over Black's game now:} Nd7 $1 $146 {Much stronger move, Black is ready for b5-Nb6.} 21. Nc3 b5 22. e4 {Maybe Grischuk was scared of e4 plans, but no need:} dxe4 23. Nxe4 h6 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] One prophlyactic move, against Ng5 ideas, and our counterplay comes.} 24. Nc5 Nb6 $15 {[%cal Gb6d5] Only Black can be slightly better here.} *

