{[%evp 0,40,22,14,23,23,30,3,3,3,-3,-4,3,3,3,-2,6,0,3,12,7,4,-1,-9,-11,-11,-2,-19,-13,-1,-4,-4,10,2,-5,-21,-4,-40,5,-65,-71,-90,-34]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. a3 Bd7 7. b4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 {[%csl Rc1,Gd4][%cal Gc6d4]} 9. Bb2 {This is White's most common continuation.} Nge7 {Our idea is to continue with Nf5, creating pressure against White's pawn on d4. But we also have the Na5-Nc4 idea.} (9... Na5 $6 {is premature because of} 10. Nbd2 {where Black tried} Nc4 {but after} 11. Nxc4 dxc4 12. Rc1 Qa6 13. d5 exd5 14. Qxd5 Ne7 15. Qd2 $1 b5 16. Be2 Be6 17. O-O $14 {Our position is unpleasant to play.}) 10. Nc3 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gc3a4,Ya4c5] White's most serious continuation. The idea is Na4-Nc5.} (10. Be2 Nf5 {Trans in 9.Be2.}) (10. Qd2 {Svidler tried this idea in 2019.} Nf5 11. g4 Nh6 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gh6f7] I prefer this move over 11...Nf7 because it is more concrete. Our idea is f6-Nf7.} (11... Nfe7 {is another possible direction. After} 12. Bd3 $132 {The position is very complex, but Black is not worse.}) 12. Rg1 (12. h3 {[%cal Ye1g1] Compared to 12.Rg1, White maintains the short castle possibility.} f6 {For example:} 13. Be2 $146 {Already a novelty for White, but it looks as the critical continuation.} Nf7 14. Nc3 fxe5 15. dxe5 Be7 16. O-O O-O 17. Rac1 {[%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5] White's idea is Na4-Nc5, and it's very important to play} (17. Na4 Qd8 18. Nc5 (18. Rac1 $6 {allows the typical trick:} Nxb4 $1 $15) 18... Bxc5 19. bxc5 Na5 $15 {[%cal Ga5c4] Nc4 next, we sacrifice the 'd' pawn, but our bishop on c6 will be very strong, especially because White has played g2-g4.}) 17... Qd8 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5] a strong prophylactic move. We are ready to continue with Bg5.} 18. Nxd5 {White's critical continuation.} (18. Na4 $6 {allows the typical trick} Nxb4 $1 $15) 18... exd5 19. Qxd5 Be8 20. Qe4 Ng5 21. Nxg5 Bxg5 22. f4 Bg6 23. Qe3 Bh4 $13 {White has compensation, but not more than that.}) 12... f6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Nc3 {White is ready for Na4-Nc5.} Ne7 $5 $146 {[%csl Ya4][%cal Rc3a4,Gd7a4] We are not allowing Na4.} (14... Nf7 {was the move played by Lupulescu against Svidler, but after} 15. Na4 $1 Qd8 16. Nc5 {might be a bit unpleasant for Black.}) 15. h4 (15. g5 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5] White plays for the e5 square.} fxg5 16. Ne5 (16. Nxg5 Nhf5 $15 {Quite comfortable for Black.}) 16... Ng6 17. Nxd7 (17. Qxg5 Qd8 $1 $11) 17... Kxd7 $13 {[%cal Gd7c7,Gc7b8] At some point, we can continue with Kc7-Kb8.}) 15... Nf7 {We have transposed into the Svidler-Lupulescu game, but with a different move order.} 16. Bd3 Bg7 17. Ne2 e5 $1 18. dxe5 fxe5 {White is already worse, but the position is very complicated:} 19. Nf4 Rf8 (19... O-O $5 {Was another possibility, but I can understand why Black didn't go for it.} 20. Nh5 Bh8 21. Bf5 Rfd8 22. Ng5 Nxf5 23. gxf5 Bxf5 24. Ne6+ Bg6 25. Nxd8 Rxd8 26. Ng3 Qf6 $36 {The engine thinks that Black is preferable.} 27. h5 Ng5 $1 $15) 20. g5 {[%cal Gd3h7] White prepares Bxh7.} (20. Bxh7 $4 Qh6 $19 {White lost a piece.}) 20... Kd8 $5 $146 {Lupulescu has chosen 20...d4, but maybe Kd8 was the best.} 21. Rd1 {This position is very complicated, and it's difficult to say who is risking more. Let me show you the best line, according to the engine.} (21. Bxh7 d4 22. Nh5 Nd6 $1 $17) 21... d4 22. g6 Bh6 $1 23. Bxd4 exd4 24. gxf7 Rxf7 25. Ng5 Bxg5 26. Rxg5 Qf6 27. Nh5 Qf3 28. Ng3 Nc6 $36) (10. Nbd2 $6 {This is not a good move for concrete reasons:} Nf5 11. Nb3 a5 $1 {very important idea to remember.} 12. b5 (12. g4 $5 {Has been played only once in 1984.} axb4 $1 13. gxf5 bxa3 14. Rxa3 Bb4+ 15. Nfd2 Bxa3 16. Bxa3 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 $13 {Very difficult to say who is risking more, objectively the position is balanced, but practically open for all the three results.}) 12... a4 $1 (12... Na7 $2 {Would be a huge positional mistake, because after} 13. a4 $1 $16 {White is strategically much better.}) 13. g4 $1 {Only move for White.} (13. Nc5 $4 Ncxd4 14. Nxd7 Qa5+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16. Nxd2 Kxd7 $19) (13. bxc6 Bxc6 $15) 13... Nd8 $3 14. gxf5 Bxb5 {We will for sure recover the piece, and have a better position. For example:} 15. Nc5 Bxf1 16. Nxa4 Qb5 $1 17. Rxf1 Rc4 $15) (10. Bd3 Na5 (10... Nf5 $5 {is another possible direction, for example:} 11. Bxf5 exf5 12. Nc3 Be6 13. O-O Be7 {It's not clear if White is able to find good ideas here, but I can understand that not everybody would like to play this structure with Black.}) 11. O-O (11. Nbd2 $6 Nc4 {White cannot now take Nxc4 because dxc4 would come with tempo.} 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Rc1 Qa6 14. Ne4 Nd5 15. O-O Bc6 $15 {[%csl Gc6] Black is strategically better because the bishop on c6 is very strong.}) (11. Nc3 {will be analyzed via the 10.Nc3 move order.}) 11... Nc4 12. Bc1 $6 Nf5 $1 13. Bxf5 exf5 {maybe you don't like this structure, but this is a very good version because our knight is already on c4:} 14. Nc3 Be6 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black can just continue with h6-Be7-00, for example:} 15. Na4 Qc6 16. Nc5 b6 $1 (16... h6 $6 {Liu-Goganov, 2017.} 17. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 18. Nh4 $1 $16) 17. Nxe6 fxe6 $11 {Be7-00 next, and Black is doing great.}) 10... Na5 {White wants to have a knight on c5, and we want to have a knight on c4.} 11. Na4 {White's main idea.} (11. Rc1 $6 Nc4 12. Bxc4 Rxc4 $15 {Black is just better from the strategic point of view.}) (11. Nd2 $6 Nc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Nde4 Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Nc5 {Negi-Ding, 2012.} Bf5 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gb6g6,Ge8g8]}) (11. Bd3 $5 {This move was tried in the very important game Pragg-Berkes, World-Cup 2023.} Nc4 12. Bc1 (12. Bxc4 $6 {Just a bad move from the strategic point of view.} Rxc4 $15 {Black is better because we have the c4 square, and White's light squares are weak.}) 12... Nxe5 $1 $146 {In my opinion, Black should accept the pawn sacrifice.} (12... a5 {Was the move chosen by Berkes, and we will speak about it in the model game.}) 13. dxe5 Rxc3 {[%cal Gd7b5] If we can play Bb5, our position will be basically winning.} 14. Be3 $1 (14. O-O $2 Rxd3 15. Qxd3 Bb5 $17 {White is much worse because he doesn't have compensation for the missing pawn.}) 14... Qd8 $1 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc3c8] We keep the c8 retreat square free for our rook.} (14... Qc7 $6 {Looks logical, but it's not the best:} 15. O-O $1 $14 {[%csl Rc3] Bd4 next, and our rook on c3 becomes a target.}) 15. O-O (15. Qd2 Rc8 16. O-O a6 {[%cal Gd7b5] our idea is Bb5.} 17. a4 (17. Rfc1 Ba4 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Rc1 Nc6 20. Nd4 Qd7 21. Nxc6 Bxc6 22. Qc3 Be7 23. Bxa6 O-O $11) 17... d4 $1 18. Bxd4 (18. Nxd4 Nd5 $11) 18... Bc6 19. Rfc1 g6 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Bg7-00 next.}) 15... a6 {[%cal Gc3d3,Gd7b5] With the idea Rxd3-Qxd3-Bb5.} 16. a4 Nc6 $1 17. b5 Nb4 18. Be2 Be7 {White has compensation, but not more:} 19. Rb1 (19. Nd4 {White plays for compensation, but it's just a position:} O-O 20. Qd2 Rc7 21. Bf4 a5 22. Ra3 Nc2 23. Rg3 Nxd4 24. Qxd4 Bh4 25. Rc3 Rxc3 26. Qxc3 f6 $11) 19... axb5 20. Bd2 Na2 $1 21. axb5 (21. Rxb5 O-O 22. Rxb7 Bc6 23. Rb2 Ra3 $11) 21... O-O 22. Rb3 Qc7 $1 23. Bxc3 Nxc3 24. Qc2 Nxe2+ 25. Qxe2 Qc4 $1 $44 {Black has full compensation for the exchange.}) 11... Qc6 12. Nc5 Nc4 {This is a very important position for the evaluation of the variation.} 13. Bc1 {[%cal Gc1h6] From c1 the bishop still has an influence on the kingside.} (13. Bxc4 $2 {a huge positional mistake.} dxc4 14. Rc1 b6 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Nd2 b5 17. Ne4 Nd5 $17 {Abdraluf-Kakabayev, 2023.}) (13. Qb1 $6 {Was tried by a young Schevchenko, but after} b6 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 {Black's position is already more comfortable:} 15. Bc1 b5 16. Bd3 {Shevchenko-Agmanov, 2018.} Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gh7h6,Ge8g8] Be7-h6-00 next.}) (13. Qb3 b6 14. Nxd7 (14. Nd3 Qa4 $1 $15) 14... Qxd7 15. Bd3 b5 $11 {[%cal Ge7c6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] just Nc6-Be7-00 next.}) (13. Bc3 $5 {Compared to 13.Bc1, the bishop on c3 may be useful against a5, or in the case of f5-exf6-Bxf6, White's pawn on d4 will be more protected.} b6 14. Nxd7 Qxd7 15. Bd3 g6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gf8h6] Strong play shown by Pragg. As White's bishop is on c3, Black idea is to continue with h5-Bh6.} 16. Bd2 $1 {Is White's best, according to the engine, but it's a very difficult move to play because it allows} (16. O-O h5 $132 {[%cal Gf8h6] Bh6 next, and it's absolutely fine for Black.}) (16. Qe2 h5 17. Bd2 Nxd2 18. Nxd2 Bh6 $15 {Pragg-Caruana, 2024.}) 16... Nb2 17. Qe2 Nxd3+ 18. Qxd3 {[%csl Rg6] Normally, Black is better in these positions, but here our g6 move created some weaknesses.} Bg7 19. O-O Rc4 20. a4 (20. Rfc1 b5 $132) 20... O-O 21. b5 a6 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8a8] Ra8 next.}) 13... b6 14. Nxd7 (14. Nb3 $2 {This is not how White should play, after} Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gd7a4] Black will continue with Ba4 and a5, and our position is already better.}) 14... Qxd7 15. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3] Most natural square for White's bishop.} (15. Be2 {Is a timid move. Obviously, White's bishop is much better placed on d3, so we don't need to analyze it.}) 15... b5 16. h4 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White's only interesting plan is to take space on the kingside. If White does something else, we just play Be7-00 with a good and comfortable position.} (16. O-O Nc6 17. h4 {trans.}) 16... Nc6 17. h5 {[%csl Gh5] Normal positional move.} (17. O-O Be7 (17... h6 $6 {was played by L'Ami, but the pawn on h6 is not always well placed (White might have Bxh6 sacrifices). For example:} 18. h5 Be7 19. Nh2 O-O 20. Qg4 $14 {Dangerous position for Black.}) 18. h5 {Black doesn't need to hurry with castle.} a6 $5 $132 {[%cal Yf7f5,Ye7d8,Yd8b6] Is a useful move. We can slowly continue with Bd8-Bb6, eventually with f5.}) 17... Be7 $1 {Correctly, Berkes does not play h6.} 18. Rh3 (18. Kf1 f5 $1 {Similar to Vitiugov-Berkes.}) 18... f5 $1 19. exf6 $1 {White had to take on f6.} (19. Bb1 $6 {positional mistake.} a5 $15 {Vitiugov-Berkes, 2023.}) 19... Bxf6 20. Bb1 Nd6 $132 {00 next. Normal position where we can play for three results.} *

