{[%evp 0,28,25,16,41,28,33,22,22,34,31,38,7,22,27,-1,-11,-54,-25,-13,-1,0,0,-2,31,33,40,21,17,-1,28]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 {I play the French exchange with White and Black, and very rarely it ends with a boring draw.} 4. Nf3 {[%csl Gf3] This is White's most natural move and also the best one, in my opinion.} (4. Qf3 {[%csl Rf3] rare move, because f3 is a square for the knight, not for the queen.} Nf6 {[%cal Gc8g4] we are ready for Bg4.} 5. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4] White prevents Bg4.} (5. Bd3 $6 {allowing Bg4 is not a good strategy for White.} Bg4 6. Qg3 Nc6 7. c3 Qd7 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] 000 next.}) 5... c5 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Rf3] we play c7-c5, using the misplaced position of White's queen.} 6. Bb5+ {best option for White, but just to equalize:} (6. dxc5 Bxc5 $15 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ge8g8,Yf8e8] 00-Re8 next, and Black is better because Qf3 is misplaced.}) 6... Nc6 7. Ne2 Qb6 {the most concrete, but other moves were also possible.} 8. Nbc3 cxd4 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 Bc5 $132 {[%cal Gc8e6] Be6 next. Maybe it's equal, or maybe we are preferable, but for sure we are fine.}) (4. Bf4 {White wants to exchange the bishops in case of Bd6.} Bd6 5. Qd2 {[%cal Yb1c3,Ye1c1] White's plan is Nc3-000.} (5. Bxd6 {this is harmless because we will have easy development:} Qxd6 6. c3 Nf6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 Bg4 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Yg4h5] Nbd7, eventually Bh5 next.}) 5... Nf6 ({I don't recommend} 5... Bxf4 6. Qxf4 $14 {[%csl Gf4] because White's queen is too active on f4.}) 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O-O {[%cal Yf2f3,Yg2g4] White usually wants to take some space on the kingside with f3-g4.} a5 $5 $146 {[%csl Ga5] I like this move because we can start a queenside counterplay.} 8. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4] f3-g4 is White's standard and best approach.} (8. Bd3 Na6 $36) 8... c6 9. Bxd6 {it's better for White to exchange immediately on d6.} (9. g4 {normal move, but after} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Rf4d6,Ge8d6] whenever White will capture on d6, we will recapture with the knight.} 10. h4 (10. Bxd6 Nxd6 $15 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb7b5]}) 10... b5 $132 {[%cal Ga5a4,Yb5b4] it's easier for Black to organize an attack, just a4-b4 next.}) 9... Qxd6 10. g4 b5 11. Nh3 {[%cal Gd2f4] White prepares Qf4.} (11. h4 {too slow:} a4 12. Nh3 b4 13. Ne2 Na6 $36) 11... a4 12. Qf4 Qe7 (12... Qd8 {I don't like it because White can play} 13. a3 $1 {[%cal Gc3a2] with Na2 idea. The engine thinks that we are fine after 13...b4, but it could become tricky.}) 13. Bd3 (13. a3 $2 {[%csl Ge7] with the queen on e7 it's bad:} b4 $17) 13... b4 14. Rhe1 Be6 15. Ne2 Nbd7 $132 {Balanced position for three results.}) (4. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2] White can play with Bd3-Ne2, but it's harmless:} Bd6 5. Ne2 Nf6 {[%csl Gf6] When White's knight is on f3, we will develop the knight on e7, but now that White's knight is on e2, we will go on f6.} 6. O-O O-O 7. Bf4 (7. c3 Bg4 $11 {[%cal Yg4h5,Yh5g6] Bh5-Bg6 next.}) 7... Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 9. c3 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e2] we can think about Rxe2, that's why Bxd6 is necessary for White.} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11) (4. c4 {The Panov system is not interesting against the French:} Nf6 {compared to QGA for Black, we don't even need to develop our bishop on d6 here.} (4... dxc4 5. Bxc4 Bd6 {we have seen this position in my database QGA for Black, and Black was absolutely fine.}) 5. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Gb4] Nobody plays like this with White because Black is doing great with very simple moves. I will show you how usually the game continues:} 6. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2] White starts with Bd3 if he wants to develop the knight on e2.} (6. Nf3 O-O {we wait for White to move the bishop, and only later will we capture on c4.} 7. Be2 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bg4 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Qd6 $11 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Ga8d8,Ya8e8] Rad8 or Rae8 next.}) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 O-O 8. Nge2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gc7c6] we will continue with Nbd7-c6.} 9. O-O Nb6 10. Bb3 c6 11. Bg5 (11. Qd3 Re8 $11 {[%cal Gc8e6] Be6 next.}) 11... Re8 {[%cal Gc8e6] we prepare Be6.} 12. Nf4 {[%cal Rc8e6,Gf4h5] White prevents Be6 and threats Nh5.} (12. Qd3 h6 13. Bh4 Be6 $11) 12... Qd6 $11 {[%cal Gc8g4,Yh7h6] h6 or Bg4 next.}) 4... Bd6 {When I am White, I play here 5.Bd3, but 5.c4 is more popular nowadays.} 5. c4 {This is how top players usually play nowadays.} (5. Bd3 {I like this continuation because Black needs experience and preparation to fully equalize.} Nc6 {[%csl Gc6] I recommend to play Nc6.} (5... Ne7 {this is possible, but after} 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 $5 {[%cal Gc3b5] is interesting for White, with the idea Nb5.} c6 {normal move against Nb5.} (7... a6 8. Ng5 $36) 8. Ng5 $5 {I have suggested this for White in my Modern Chess course "Exchange French for White", published in July 2024. If Black plays like an engine, he can equalize, but it's not easy, and I like White here.}) 6. O-O (6. c3 Nge7 7. Qc2 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rc8f5] White prevents Bf5, but the queen on c2 might be misplaced.} h6 8. O-O O-O {[%cal Ge7g6] and I am ready to play Ng6 next, for example:} 9. h3 (9. Re1 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gd8f6] same idea as after 9.h3.} 10. Bxg6 fxg6 11. Qxg6 Bf5 12. Qh5 Qd7 $36) 9... Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gd8f6] Qf6 will be my next move, and I already prefer Black.} 10. Bxg6 $2 {would be a huge mistake:} fxg6 11. Qxg6 Rxf3 12. gxf3 Qh4 $18) 6... Nge7 7. c3 {most common and natural move.} (7. Nc3 {not dangerous now:} a6 8. Re1 (8. a3 Bg4 $132 {[%csl Rd4]}) 8... Nb4 $11 {Nxd3 next, or Bf5 if White retreats the bishop.}) (7. Re1 O-O 8. c3 Bf5 $11) 7... Bf5 $1 {this is the most accurate continuation. Of course, exchanging the bishops is nice, but the big question is to understand if it works against White's concrete tries.} (7... O-O {would be nice, but as I indicate in my course "Exchange French for White", after} 8. Nh4 $1 $40 {White gets a strong kingside initiative.}) (7... Bg4 {this is Black's most common continuation, but I believe that here White gets an interesting game after} 8. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Yd2f1,Yf1e3] Re1-Nf1-Ne3 next.}) 8. Bxf5 {only critical move.} (8. Re1 {harmless:} O-O 9. Bxf5 (9. Bg5 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8]}) 9... Nxf5 10. Qd3 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8] Rae8 next.}) 8... Nxf5 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Rb7] we need to spend another tempo to protect b7.} (9. Re1+ Nce7 10. Qb3 $1 b6 {leads to the same as 9.Qb3.}) 9... b6 10. Re1+ {critical position.} Nce7 $1 {[%csl Ge7,Rf5] This is the best. It's a bit strange because the knight on f5 looks very shaky, but it works concretely.} (10... Nfe7 {is the most natural continuation, but White gets an intersting game after} 11. c4 $5 O-O 12. Bg5 $132) 11. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Gb3d5] According to the engines, Kh1 is White's best move, because now Qxd5 is a threat.} (11. c4 O-O 12. Bg5 {this was interesting against 10...Nfe7, but now} (12. Nc3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 Qd7 14. Bg5 (14. g4 $6 Nh6 $1 $36 {[%csl Rg4]}) 14... Rfe8 $11 {[%cal Ge7g6] Ng6 next and no problems.}) 12... f6 $132 {[%csl Gf5] the knight on f5 is much better placed.}) (11. g4 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Rg4] very important, we are not afraid of Bxh6.} 12. Bxh6 gxh6 $132 {[%csl Rf4,Rg4] We are not worse because White has problems with g4 and with the f4 square.}) 11... O-O 12. g4 {g4 is more critical now than on move 11, because we have already played castle.} Nh6 13. Bxh6 gxh6 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gg8h8,Yf8g8] Still, we are fine, and the engine even slightly prefers Black. Qd7-Kh8-Rg8 next, for example.}) 5... Nf6 {if you don't want to transpose in QGA for Black, you can also play Nf6.} ({You can also play} 5... dxc4 {because after} 6. Bxc4 Nf6 {we transpose to QGA for Black, and we have already seen on that occasion that Black is doing great here.}) 6. c5 {modern continuation, more interesting than 6.Nc3.} (6. Nc3 {old continuation, but harmless.} O-O ({also} 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 O-O 8. O-O Nc6 $11 {we transpose in a good line of QGA for Black.}) 7. cxd5 (7. c5 {transposes in 6.c5 Be7 7.Nc3.}) 7... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5] we simply want to play Nb6-Nbxd5.} 8. Bg5 (8. Bc4 $6 Re8+ $1 9. Be3 Ng4 10. O-O Rxe3 11. fxe3 Nxe3 12. Qd3 Nxf1 13. Rxf1 Nf6 $15) (8. Bd3 $6 Re8+ 9. Be3 Nb6 $15 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gb6d5] White's bishop on e3 is misplaced once we play Nbxd5.}) (8. Be2 h6 $132 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gd7b6,Gb6d5,Rc1g5] we prevent Bg5 and will continue with Nb6-Nbxd5 next.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 Nb6 10. Be2 Be7 {[%cal Gf6d5] we are ready for Nfxd5.} (10... g5 $6 11. Bg3 $1 $14) 11. Bxf6 (11. O-O Nfxd5 $11) 11... Bxf6 12. Qb3 a5 13. a4 Bf5 14. O-O Qd6 $132 {[%cal Gd6b4,Yf8d8] Rfd8 or Qb4 next, and we are doing great.}) 6... Be7 {[%cal Gb7b6] our idea is now b6, and White should find a clever move against it.} 7. Qa4+ $5 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Rb7b6] This is considered the most interesting continuation for White.} (7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Be3 (9. b4 a5 $1 $15) (9. cxb6 axb6 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6] c5-Nc6 next.}) 9... bxc5 10. dxc5 a5 {very useful move, and we can continue with Ba6 or Bg4, according to the situation:} (10... Bg4 $6 11. Nbd2 $1 $14) 11. Nbd2 (11. Nc3 Bg4 $1 $11 {compared to the immediate 10...Bg4, here White cannot play Nbd2.}) 11... Ba6 $11) (7. Bb5+ $6 {not a clever move against b6.} c6 8. Bd3 b6 9. cxb6 axb6 10. O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Yc8g4,Yc8a6] Bg4 or Ba6 next.}) (7. Nc3 {standard continuation, but not interesting for White:} O-O {[%cal Gb7b6] b6 next.} 8. Bd3 b6 9. cxb6 axb6 10. O-O c5 11. h3 Nc6 12. Be3 Re8 $11 {equal position.}) 7... Bd7 ({after the natural} 7... c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O b6 {[%csl Ga4] White's queen is on a4, and it means that after} 10. cxb6 $14 {[%cal Ra4a8] we cannot recapture on b6 with the pawn. This is the main idea of 7.Qa4+!?.}) 8. Qc2 (8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb3] doesn't make sense, because after} b6 $15 {[%csl Rc5] White's c5 pawn is not protected.}) 8... O-O 9. Be3 (9. Bd3 $6 {not good for concrete reasons:} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 10. a3 (10. O-O Nb4 $15) 10... Re8 $1 $146 11. O-O Bg4 {[%csl Rd4] White has problems with d4.} 12. Nbd2 Ne4 $1 {now starts a forced line:} 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Nxd4 16. Qd1 Bxc5 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Ba6 Qh4 $15 {[%csl Gb8,Gc5,Gd4,Ge8,Gh4] our pieces are very active.}) 9... Re8 $1 $146 {Strong Novelty. Re8 is a very useful move, and we will act according to White's next move.} (9... b6 10. Nc3 {[%csl Rc5] c5 is defended, and I don't like the bxc5-dxc5 structure.}) (9... Qc8 $6 {immediately it is not good:} 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. a3 $14) 10. Be2 {White gives priority to the development, but with Be2 only because Bd3 is bad for concrete reasons.} (10. Bd3 $6 {mistake, and this is the idea behind 9...Re8:} Nc6 $1 11. a3 Ng4 $1 $15) (10. Nc3 Qc8 $1 {[%cal Gd7f5] we want to play Bf5.} 11. Bd3 {[%csl Rc3,Ge8] thanks to the inclusion of the moves Re8 and Nc3, we are now in time to equalize with} (11. b4 {normal positional continuation.} Nc6 12. b5 Bf5 13. Qa4 Nd8 14. Be2 c6 15. O-O Ne4 $132 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gd8e6] Bf6-Ne6 next.}) 11... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 12. a3 Bxc5 $1 13. dxc5 d4 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Ge8]}) 10... Qc8 $5 {[%cal Gd7f5] my idea is to play Bf5. Once we play it, our position will be absolutely fine, for example:} 11. Bd3 $5 {This is White's best, in my opinion.} (11. O-O Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gb8d7] c6-Nbd7 next.}) (11. b4 {positional continuation.} Bf5 12. Qb2 c6 13. Nc3 Nbd7 14. O-O Ne4 $11) 11... a6 $1 {[%cal Gd7b5] we prepare Bb5.} (11... Nc6 12. a3 $14 {[%csl Yb1][%cal Re7c5] White's knight is still on b1, and we don't have the Bxc5-dxc5-d4 idea.}) 12. O-O (12. a4 $2 {huge positional mistake.} a5 $15 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb8c6,Gc6b4] Nc6-Nb4 next.}) (12. Nc3 {allows the typical tactical idea} Nc6 13. a3 Bxc5 $1 14. dxc5 d4 $11) 12... Bb5 13. Bxb5 axb5 14. Nc3 c6 $11 {Black is doing great. In conclusion, against White's modern 5.c4 try, we can choose between the classical 5...Nf6, or 5...dxc4, which would transpose into the QGA for Black.} *

