{[%evp 0,38,22,12,43,33,36,-3,-9,-12,-12,-5,-9,-18,-18,-7,6,25,25,25,22,-5,-6,-7,0,1,-11,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-14,-11,-12,-20,-15,-15]} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 {A harmless variation, but it is still occasionally played by "lazy players" who prefer to avoid studying more theory-intensive lines against the French.} dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 (5. Bd3 $6 {doesn't make any sense.} c5 $1 $36 {Black is immediately fine, and you don't need to know anything more. We have a lot of extra tempi compared to many other lines.}) 5... c5 {[%csl Gf3] White's hope is that the bishop on f3 will become active eventually, but the main issue is that f3 is the ideal square for the knight on g1. Additionally, the bishop on f3 could become a target, for example, after Nc6-Ne5 or e5-e4.} 6. Ne2 (6. c3 {harmless because of} cxd4 7. cxd4 Bd6 {and Black is immediately doing fine, for example:} 8. Ne2 h6 $5 {[%cal Rc1g5] useful move that stops Bg5 ideas.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Nbc3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8]} 11. Be3 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ga8c8] We can continue with Rc8-Nce7, and we have a great version of the isolated pawn structure. If White plays d5, Ne5 will always be an option for us.}) (6. Be3 $6 {also dubious:} cxd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Bxd4 Be7 8. Ne2 O-O 9. O-O Qc7 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3][%cal Gb8c6,Yc6e5] Nc6-Ne5 next, and both White's bishops are misplaced.}) 7... Qxd4 8. Bxd4 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Rf3] White's bishops are misplaced. If White plays Be3 or Bc3, we can also consider the Nd5 idea. (or Nb4-Nbd5).}) 6... Nc6 {I like the classical 6...Nc6.} (6... cxd4 $6 {now it's not good:} 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Rb8c6] compared to the 6.Be3 variation, now White has a knight on d4 and not a bishop, which means that we cannot play Nc6.}) (6... Be7 {is another good direction for Black.}) 7. Be3 (7. c3 cxd4 8. cxd4 h6 $132 {very similar to the 6.c3 variation.}) 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Ne5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rf3] very important move. We use the misplaced position of Bf3.} 9. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1c1] White's most interesting idea is to continue with Qe2-000.} (9. Be2 $6 {harmless, because then all the 3.Bd3 system didn't make any sense.} Bb4+ $5 {I like to provoke c2-c3, so that White will not be able to develop with Nc3.} 10. c3 Be7 {[%cal Rb1c3]} 11. O-O Nd5 {[%csl Re3]} 12. Bc1 O-O $36) (9. O-O {when White plays short castle, our position is always fine in the 3.Bd3 variation:} a6 10. Nc3 Qc7 {Black's best, according to the engine. The only minus is that you should remember how to play against White's concrete attempts, but that's not too difficult:} ({maybe there is no need to deal with the concrete lines of 10...Qc7.} 10... Bd6 $5 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rad1 Qc7 $132) 11. Bf4 Bd6 12. Ndb5 $5 (12. Kh1 {White steps away for Nxf3+.} O-O 13. Qe2 (13. Ncb5 $4 axb5 14. Nxb5 Qc4 $19 {[%csl Rf4] Bf4 is hanging.}) 13... Nxf3 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nxf3 Qb6 $15 {[%cal Gc8d7] Bd7 next, and our French bishop will become very strong soon.}) 12... axb5 13. Nxb5 Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 Bxf4 15. Nxc7+ Bxc7 $15 {Funny position, but Black is slightly better, according to the engine.}) 9... a6 {[%csl Ga6] a6 is always useful, so that we can continue with Qc7 without thinking about Nb5 moves.} (9... Be7 10. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next.}) (9... Nxf3+ $2 {is a huge mistake.} 10. Qxf3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1] 000 next, and White's pieces are too active.}) 10. Qe2 (10. O-O Qc7 $132 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gf8d6] when White plays Short Castle, we are always fine.}) 10... Nxf3+ $1 {only now, when a6 is included, we will take on f3.} 11. Qxf3 {[%cal Ge1c1] the most critical recapture.} (11. gxf3 {possible, but not critical.} Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. O-O-O Bd7 (13... Qxa2 $6 14. Nb3 $36) 14. Kb1 Be7 $132 {White has a bad structure, and we have two bishops. For now, it might be equal, but in the future, it could easily become better for Black.}) (11. Nxf3 {not critical:} b5 {[%cal Re1c1] White cannot play 000.} 12. Bd4 Bb7 13. O-O-O Qc7 {[%cal Gf8e7] we are ready to continue with Be7. The only continuation that deserves to be mentioned is} 14. Be5 Qc8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Ne4 {but we are fine in more than one way, for example:} Bh6+ 17. Kb1 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 O-O $11 {[%cal Gh6g7,Gf6f5] Bg7-f5 next.}) 11... e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] very important move.} 12. Nb3 {probably the best.} (12. O-O-O $2 {doesn't work.} Bg4 $1 13. Qxb7 exd4 $1 $146 (13... Bxd1 $2 14. Rxd1 $40) 14. Rhe1 Qc8 $19) (12. Nf5 $6 {looks active, but after} Qa5 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ga5f5,Ye5e4] we are ready to play e4 and White has concrete problems with Nf5.} 13. Ng3 (13. O-O-O $4 e4 $1 $19 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ga5f5] White lost a piece.}) (13. g4 e4 $1 14. Qf4 Nxg4 $1 15. Qxe4+ Qe5 $15) 13... Bb4 $15 {[%csl Rc3]}) (12. Nde2 {too passive.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc8e6,Yf8e7,Ye8g8,Ya8c8] we will play normal moves like Be6-Be7-00-Rc8-b5. In which order? Depends on how White plays, but our position is more than fine.} 13. O-O-O Be6 $132 14. Bg5 {important to remember to play} Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8,Yf7f6,Yf8e7] just Rc8-f6-Be7 next, for example:} (14... Be7 $6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. Rxd5 O-O 18. Nc3 $14 {/=. We are very solid, but White has a risk-free position.}) 15. Nd5 Qc6 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 16. Rd2 f6 17. Be3 Rc8 18. Rhd1 b5 $36) 12... Bb4 {[%csl Rc3] we can play against Nc3.} 13. Bc5 {White plays 13.Bc5 if he doesn't want to allow the Bxc3-bxc3 structure.} (13. Bd2 $6 {too passive:} O-O 14. O-O Be6 $15) (13. O-O Bxc3 $1 {First, we ruin White's structure.} 14. bxc3 O-O 15. Rad1 Qc7 {very good for Black, for example:} 16. Bg5 Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f6] f6 next.} (16... Bg4 $2 17. Qg3 Bxd1 18. Bxf6 $18) 17. Bd8 (17. Rfe1 Be6 18. h3 f6 19. Bc1 Rf7 $15 {[%csl Rc2,Rc3][%cal Gf7d7,Ge8d6] long terms problems for White because of the structure.}) 17... Bg4 $1 18. Qxg4 (18. Bxc7 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Nxc7 $36 {White has a very bad structure for a knight endgame.}) 18... Rxd8 19. Rxd8 Qxd8 $11 {Equal, but still playable.}) 13... Bxc5 14. Nxc5 O-O 15. O-O Qc7 {This is minimum equal for us.} 16. N5e4 (16. Nb3 $6 b6 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7] Bb7 next.}) (16. Nd3 Be6 17. Rfe1 Nd7 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Rfe8 20. Rad1 Rad8 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gg8g7] g6-Kg7 next, and we improve the position.}) 16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Be6 $11 {It's equal, but still playable. Gukesh had this position with Black in 2022, and he won.} *

