{[%evp 0,20,25,20,33,1,1,-5,14,14,14,-6,-14,-14,-15,-15,-10,-3,1,7,-14,-8,-5]} 1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 {This system is not critical objectively, but White can choose it if he likes this type of positions (Nf3-g3-Bg2-00 next, and then King's Indian attack style). Against this approach, I also want to play something that I like.} g6 $5 {This is how I want to approach this variation.} (3... c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {is the main continuation. White will soon push e4-e5. Black is not worse, but you need to have some experience to play it.}) 4. Ngf3 (4. g3 {White can delay Nf3 only if he thinks about playing f2-f4, but that's not good:} Bg7 5. Bg2 Ne7 6. f4 $6 dxe4 $1 7. dxe4 e5 $1 {[%csl Rf4]} 8. Ngf3 exf4 9. gxf4 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ye4e5,Ye7f5] Bb7 next, and Black is already preferable. Whenever White will play e4-e5, we will have a good square on f5 for our knight.}) 4... Bg7 5. g3 {standard continuation in the KIA.} (5. h4 $5 $146 {has never been tried, but better to check it.} Nc6 6. h5 g5 {[%cal Gf7f5] We can already think about f5.} 7. d4 {only move for White not to get worse.} (7. Be2 f5 $1 $15) 7... f5 $5 {concrete idea.} (7... h6 {[%cal Gg8e7] Nge7 next. This is also good.}) 8. exf5 exf5 9. Bb5 Qe7+ $1 {important move.} 10. Qe2 Qxe2+ 11. Kxe2 h6 12. Ne5 Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Nxc6 bxc6 $11 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gg8f6] Kd7-Nf6 next, and no problem for Black.}) (5. d4 {engine's recommendation, but it cannot be a problem because White wasted one tempo for d3.} Ne7 6. e5 $146 {this is how the engine plays, but there are no games.} (6. c3 {White can try to play without e5.} O-O 7. Be2 c5 $1 8. e5 {only move not to get slightly worse with White.} (8. dxc5 Nd7 $36 {[%cal Gd7c5] Nxc5 next. The engine already prefers Black.}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 f6 {[%csl Ye7,Gf6] typical idea when our knight is on e7.} 10. exf6 Bxf6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge7f5] Nbc6-Nf5 next, with a good game.}) 6... O-O 7. c3 (7. Nb3 {White stops c5.} Nd7 {[%cal Gc7c5] we insist on c7-c5 idea.} 8. Bd3 (8. c3 {transposes in 7.c3.}) 8... c5 $1 9. Nxc5 Nxc5 10. dxc5 Nc6 11. Qe2 f6 12. exf6 Qxf6 $44 {Full compensation, for example:} 13. c3 (13. O-O $4 e5 $19) 13... e5 14. Bg5 Qf7 15. Bc2 e4 16. Nd2 Ne5 17. O-O Bg4 18. Qe3 Rae8 $44) 7... c5 8. Nb3 {we are following the engine's recommendations for White.} (8. Be2 cxd4 9. cxd4 f6 $11 {no problem for Black.}) (8. dxc5 $2 Nd7 $15 {[%csl Re5] White will lose the important e5 pawn.}) 8... cxd4 (8... c4 {possible but I don't like it.}) 9. cxd4 Nd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Ge7c6] we play Nd7 because our other knight will go to c6.} 10. Bb5 $1 {only an engine can play like this, but we can still have a comfortable position:} (10. Be2 f6 $11) 10... f6 11. Bxd7 Bxd7 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. O-O Ba4 $5 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge7f5] Qb6-Nf5 next. Engine shows +0,20, but White had to play a lot of hard moves that have never been played so far, and it's clear to me that we have enough counterplay and a position for three results. I am not worried about this +0,20.}) 5... Ne7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {[%cal Ge4e5,Yf7f6] Compared to the standard King's Indian attack, with our Knight on e7 we have the idea that whenever White pushes e4-e5, we can continue with f7-f6.} a5 $5 {[%csl Ga5] a5 is always useful for us.} (7... c5 {This allows} 8. exd5 exd5 9. Nb3 $5 {[%csl Rc5] White has some play against c5.} b6 10. d4 $14) 8. Re1 (8. exd5 exd5 $11) (8. a4 {with a5-a4 included, we can go for} dxe4 9. dxe4 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6,Gd7c5] b6-Ba6-Nc5 next.}) 8... a4 $132 {I am happy to play it. Let me show you one idea:} 9. e5 {standard continuation in the King's Indian Attack.} c5 10. c3 {and now we can play Nec6, not Nbc6.} Nec6 $5 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf7f6] Nb8 can go to d7, and then we can play f6.} *

