{[%evp 0,38,25,22,20,7,7,7,7,6,19,4,4,-5,-23,-10,-17,-1,-1,-1,5,5,5,2,5,0,22,22,26,-15,-23,-23,-23,-17,-16,-16,-5,-5,-5,-5,24]} 1. e4 e6 2. Qe2 {Funny move. White stops d5, and this is the main idea, but Qe2 can easily become misplaced.} c5 {[%csl Re2] I recommend to "transpose" into the Sicilian because White's queen on e2 cannot be critical against it.} 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 {standard continuation.} (4. c3 {White wants to play d4, but now we can finally go for} d5 {[%cal Rb1c3] the key point is that after exd5-Qxd5, White no longer has Nc3.} 5. exd5 Qxd5 {[%cal Rb1c3]} 6. g3 {you can play in many ways, but I like} b6 $5 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gg8f6,Gf8e7] Nf6-Be7 next, very simple play.}) 4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O (6. h4 {not good, but it's important to mention it.} h6 {[%csl Rh4,Gh6] the inclusion of h4-h6 is good for us.} 7. O-O (7. h5 $2 g5 $15) 7... d6 $132 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Nge7-00 next. I don't know why White has played h4.}) 6... Nge7 {White has two strategies: playing simply with d3 in KIA style, or trying to push d4 with some preparation.} 7. c3 {this is the only serious thing that we should study.} (7. d3 {the first approach is not problematic for us:} O-O 8. c3 d6 $132 {[%csl Re2] We have a fantastic version of the Closed Sicilian, which is itself harmless, but here White's queen is on e2, which is even worse for him.}) 7... O-O 8. d4 $1 {This is White's best option, and it was often played by the Italian IM Piscopo.} (8. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c2,Gd2d4] White's idea is Nc2-d4.} b6 $5 9. Nc2 a5 $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gc8a6] We will play Ba6 next, underlining the misplaced position of Qe2.}) (8. Rd1 $6 {very common, but it's a mistake.} e5 $1 {[%csl Rd1] White cannot push d4, and the rook on d1 will be misplaced, for example:} 9. Na3 (9. d3 d5 10. Nbd2 h6 $15 {[%cal Gc8e6] Be6 next.}) 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. d3 Re8 $15) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 {critical, good but not the only way.} (9... d5 {you can also don't accept the pawn sacrifice.} 10. e5 (10. Nc3 dxe4 11. Nxe4 h6 $11 {[%cal Rc1g5,Ge7f5] against Bg5, and Nf5 next.}) 10... Nf5 11. Rd1 f6 $132 {Balanced position open for three results.}) 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Bh6 {looks to me as White's most logical continuation.} (11. Rd1 Nc6 (11... Bg7 {is also good enough for equality, but a bit boring.} 12. Nc3 d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bxd5 Qf6 $11) 12. Bh6 Bg7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge6e5] we want to play d6 or e5.} 14. e5 {critical move because it stops d6 and e5.} f6 $5 {Now, White should play precisely:} 15. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 16. Nd2 fxe5 17. Nc4 Ba6 18. Qxe5+ Kg8 19. Nd6 Qf6 $11 {[%csl Gd6] White has full compensation for the equality, but no more than that.}) 11... Bg7 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd7d6] we want to play e5 or d6, after which Black will just be better.} 13. e5 {most accurate.} (13. Nc3 $6 e5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge7c6] d6-Nc6 next.} 14. Rfd1 d6 15. Nb5 Nc6 16. Rxd6 Qa5 $15 {[%csl Gc8,Gd4,Rg2][%cal Gc6d4] the material is equal, but we have a better bishop and a kinght ready to jump on d4.}) 13... d6 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Nc3 {White has compensation, but we can just give back the pawn} Bd7 16. Bxb7 Rad8 $11 {no problems. In conclusion, the choice between 9...d5 and 9...Nxd4 is entirely up to you.} *

